WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.462 align:middle line:90%


00:00:09.462 --> 00:00:12.948 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:12.948 --> 00:00:20.929 align:middle line:90%


00:00:20.929 --> 00:00:23.220 align:middle line:10%
>> REGINA MEREDITH: Rupert
Sheldrake has done more than

00:00:23.220 --> 00:00:26.490 align:middle line:10%
nearly any scientists making
the link between science

00:00:26.490 --> 00:00:28.800 align:middle line:10%
and the field of
ubiquitous intelligence.

00:00:28.800 --> 00:00:31.830 align:middle line:10%
His groundbreaking work was
on the morphogenetic field,

00:00:31.830 --> 00:00:34.260 align:middle line:10%
where genetic history is
passed on through a field

00:00:34.260 --> 00:00:35.550 align:middle line:10%
of consciousness.

00:00:35.550 --> 00:00:38.370 align:middle line:84%
Today, Rupert is speaking about
the effects of having drifted

00:00:38.370 --> 00:00:41.310 align:middle line:84%
far away from our
spiritual moorings

00:00:41.310 --> 00:00:44.150 align:middle line:84%
into a world of
atheistic materialism,

00:00:44.150 --> 00:00:46.860 align:middle line:84%
and he makes the case for
returning to our roots.

00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:47.940 align:middle line:90%
Rupert, welcome.

00:00:47.940 --> 00:00:49.630 align:middle line:90%
We're so happy to have you here.

00:00:49.630 --> 00:00:51.699 align:middle line:84%
Thank you for taking the
tube over to meet us.

00:00:51.699 --> 00:00:53.240 align:middle line:84%
>> RUPERT SHELDRAKE:
Good to be here.

00:00:53.240 --> 00:00:54.390 align:middle line:90%
Good to be here with you.

00:00:54.390 --> 00:00:54.750 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:00:54.750 --> 00:00:55.500 align:middle line:90%
It's been a while.

00:00:55.500 --> 00:00:57.120 align:middle line:84%
I think we talked about--
it's been about eight years

00:00:57.120 --> 00:00:58.590 align:middle line:90%
since I last interviewed you.

00:00:58.590 --> 00:01:00.580 align:middle line:84%
And I love your new
work, because it's

00:01:00.580 --> 00:01:04.050 align:middle line:84%
bringing a really essential
conversation back.

00:01:04.050 --> 00:01:09.420 align:middle line:84%
And I asked you off camera
how the scientific field was

00:01:09.420 --> 00:01:13.200 align:middle line:84%
receiving your work and said,
they're primarily ignoring it.

00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:16.830 align:middle line:90%
Yet I know many scientists--

00:01:16.830 --> 00:01:20.160 align:middle line:84%
I've interviewed many, many
physicists and scientists.

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:23.375 align:middle line:84%
And yet still, even though
they can't talk about it

00:01:23.375 --> 00:01:24.750 align:middle line:84%
or acknowledge
your book, there's

00:01:24.750 --> 00:01:29.160 align:middle line:84%
this deep yearning for the
magic and mysticism and ethics

00:01:29.160 --> 00:01:31.030 align:middle line:90%
of life again.

00:01:31.030 --> 00:01:35.060 align:middle line:84%
So tell us what prompted
you to write this book.

00:01:35.060 --> 00:01:37.300 align:middle line:10%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, it's
partly that I myself,

00:01:37.300 --> 00:01:39.910 align:middle line:10%
being a scientist and also
interested in spiritual

00:01:39.910 --> 00:01:43.540 align:middle line:10%
practices, have been thinking
about the connections between

00:01:43.540 --> 00:01:45.430 align:middle line:10%
the two for years.

00:01:45.430 --> 00:01:49.150 align:middle line:84%
Most of my books are
primarily scientific.

00:01:49.150 --> 00:01:52.210 align:middle line:10%
My most recent book before
this, "Science Set Free,"

00:01:52.210 --> 00:01:55.270 align:middle line:10%
is about the dogmas of
science and how science

00:01:55.270 --> 00:01:57.100 align:middle line:10%
needs to move beyond them.

00:01:57.100 --> 00:01:59.770 align:middle line:10%
And so that's about
scientific issues.

00:01:59.770 --> 00:02:03.340 align:middle line:10%
And my previous books
are primarily on science.

00:02:03.340 --> 00:02:05.920 align:middle line:10%
So this is the first
time I've really tried

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:08.050 align:middle line:10%
to connect these two realms.

00:02:08.050 --> 00:02:08.889 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:02:08.889 --> 00:02:11.138 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: And the reason
it's possible to do it is

00:02:11.138 --> 00:02:14.050 align:middle line:84%
because there's now been a
lot of scientific research

00:02:14.050 --> 00:02:17.740 align:middle line:84%
on the effects of religious
and spiritual practices.

00:02:17.740 --> 00:02:21.430 align:middle line:84%
And on the whole, the great
majority of this research

00:02:21.430 --> 00:02:23.670 align:middle line:84%
has shown that people
who do these practices

00:02:23.670 --> 00:02:26.770 align:middle line:84%
are happier, healthier,
and even live longer.

00:02:26.770 --> 00:02:31.410 align:middle line:84%
So the positive effects of
these practices are very strong.

00:02:31.410 --> 00:02:34.290 align:middle line:84%
The other side of the
coin is that if you

00:02:34.290 --> 00:02:36.810 align:middle line:84%
don't do these things,
you're unhappier,

00:02:36.810 --> 00:02:39.120 align:middle line:84%
you're unhealthier,
and live shorter.

00:02:39.120 --> 00:02:41.370 align:middle line:84%
In other words,
militant atheism ought

00:02:41.370 --> 00:02:43.530 align:middle line:90%
to come with a health warning.

00:02:43.530 --> 00:02:44.520 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes, indeed.

00:02:44.520 --> 00:02:46.860 align:middle line:84%
In fact, you talk about
that in your book.

00:02:46.860 --> 00:02:49.200 align:middle line:84%
And it's interesting because
you've run the gamut.

00:02:49.200 --> 00:02:53.340 align:middle line:84%
You started out as an
Anglican private school boy--

00:02:53.340 --> 00:02:54.480 align:middle line:90%
well, public school here.

00:02:54.480 --> 00:02:57.630 align:middle line:84%
We call it private
school in America--

00:02:57.630 --> 00:03:00.360 align:middle line:84%
who had access to a lot of
the magical things of life,

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:02.640 align:middle line:84%
secret gardens, and
so forth Let's talk

00:03:02.640 --> 00:03:04.350 align:middle line:84%
about your upbringing
just a little

00:03:04.350 --> 00:03:07.140 align:middle line:84%
bit to lay the foundation
because of this whole notion

00:03:07.140 --> 00:03:09.680 align:middle line:90%
of coming full circle.

00:03:09.680 --> 00:03:14.750 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, I was raised
by a loving family who were

00:03:14.750 --> 00:03:16.760 align:middle line:90%
committed Christians.

00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:19.520 align:middle line:84%
My father was a herbalist
and a pharmacist

00:03:19.520 --> 00:03:23.340 align:middle line:84%
and was very
interested in plants.

00:03:23.340 --> 00:03:25.470 align:middle line:90%
So I had gardens.

00:03:25.470 --> 00:03:27.860 align:middle line:84%
He taught me about
wild flowers and trees.

00:03:27.860 --> 00:03:32.360 align:middle line:84%
I kept many, many
different kinds of pets.

00:03:32.360 --> 00:03:37.220 align:middle line:84%
My mother was very
supportive, really.

00:03:37.220 --> 00:03:39.540 align:middle line:90%
And I went to a boarding school.

00:03:39.540 --> 00:03:42.220 align:middle line:84%
And I wanted to do
biology because I wanted

00:03:42.220 --> 00:03:43.840 align:middle line:90%
to study animals and plants.

00:03:43.840 --> 00:03:47.155 align:middle line:90%


00:03:47.155 --> 00:03:48.600 align:middle line:90%
And two things happened.

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:52.150 align:middle line:84%
First of all, I began to notice
that if you study biology

00:03:52.150 --> 00:03:54.940 align:middle line:84%
as a science, the first
thing you do with the things

00:03:54.940 --> 00:03:56.860 align:middle line:90%
you're studying is kill them.

00:03:56.860 --> 00:03:59.860 align:middle line:84%
So biology, which is meant
to be the science of life,

00:03:59.860 --> 00:04:02.550 align:middle line:84%
was actually mainly about the
science of dead organisms.

00:04:02.550 --> 00:04:03.350 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:04:03.350 --> 00:04:05.350 align:middle line:84%
You talked about in that
book the vivisecting

00:04:05.350 --> 00:04:06.400 align:middle line:90%
of little animals.

00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:07.200 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes.

00:04:07.200 --> 00:04:08.680 align:middle line:90%
Vivisection is part of it.

00:04:08.680 --> 00:04:09.850 align:middle line:90%
Dissection.

00:04:09.850 --> 00:04:14.680 align:middle line:84%
You start off with dissection,
then move on to vivisection.

00:04:14.680 --> 00:04:17.380 align:middle line:84%
And at the same time,
my science teachers

00:04:17.380 --> 00:04:20.709 align:middle line:84%
made it very clear that
science equals atheism.

00:04:20.709 --> 00:04:23.890 align:middle line:84%
The scientific worldview,
the mechanistic worldview

00:04:23.890 --> 00:04:27.400 align:middle line:84%
has no space for
God or spirit in it.

00:04:27.400 --> 00:04:30.550 align:middle line:84%
The whole of nature works
like an automatic machine.

00:04:30.550 --> 00:04:32.470 align:middle line:84%
Once it's started
off, it just goes

00:04:32.470 --> 00:04:36.670 align:middle line:90%
on and on in much the same way.

00:04:36.670 --> 00:04:39.910 align:middle line:84%
And animals and plants are
treated as just machines.

00:04:39.910 --> 00:04:43.340 align:middle line:84%
And so where's the spirit,
where is the soul in all that?

00:04:43.340 --> 00:04:44.140 align:middle line:90%
Answer?

00:04:44.140 --> 00:04:45.970 align:middle line:90%
Nowhere.

00:04:45.970 --> 00:04:50.620 align:middle line:84%
So science and the way I was
taught it equaled atheism.

00:04:50.620 --> 00:04:52.630 align:middle line:84%
And so because I wanted
to be a scientist,

00:04:52.630 --> 00:04:55.210 align:middle line:84%
I sort of accepted
this package deal.

00:04:55.210 --> 00:04:56.110 align:middle line:90%
Became an atheist.

00:04:56.110 --> 00:04:59.140 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: But how was
that for you, really,

00:04:59.140 --> 00:05:02.860 align:middle line:84%
on more of an emotional
level, to make--

00:05:02.860 --> 00:05:05.560 align:middle line:84%
I mean, was it a simple
leap to become an atheist

00:05:05.560 --> 00:05:08.710 align:middle line:84%
after having had a rather
traditional upbringing, where

00:05:08.710 --> 00:05:11.110 align:middle line:84%
there were rituals and
things that you actually

00:05:11.110 --> 00:05:13.904 align:middle line:84%
believed in that were a part
of the great source of life?

00:05:13.904 --> 00:05:16.570 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, you see, one
of the things that made it easy

00:05:16.570 --> 00:05:19.390 align:middle line:84%
was the fact that the school I
went to, an Anglican boarding

00:05:19.390 --> 00:05:22.090 align:middle line:84%
school, the rituals
were compulsory.

00:05:22.090 --> 00:05:23.620 align:middle line:84%
We had to go to
chapel every Sunday.

00:05:23.620 --> 00:05:24.580 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Ah, yes.

00:05:24.580 --> 00:05:27.820 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: I was in the
school choir, the chapel choir.

00:05:27.820 --> 00:05:29.070 align:middle line:90%
I loved the music.

00:05:29.070 --> 00:05:30.130 align:middle line:90%
I loved the singing.

00:05:30.130 --> 00:05:33.379 align:middle line:84%
So becoming an atheism didn't
mean the rituals stopped.

00:05:33.379 --> 00:05:34.295 align:middle line:90%
The rituals continued.

00:05:34.295 --> 00:05:35.211 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: I see, yes.

00:05:35.211 --> 00:05:39.720 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: And so I was able
to benefit from them while,

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:42.116 align:middle line:84%
at the same time,
disbelieving in them.

00:05:42.116 --> 00:05:44.490 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Interesting, because
you almost have to create

00:05:44.490 --> 00:05:48.720 align:middle line:84%
a cognitive dissonance of sorts
as a scientist who still wishes

00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:51.310 align:middle line:84%
to maintain some of the
spiritual magic in one's life.

00:05:51.310 --> 00:05:52.110 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes.

00:05:52.110 --> 00:05:56.930 align:middle line:84%
Well, I mean, I just took
it as an aesthetic pleasure.

00:05:56.930 --> 00:06:00.120 align:middle line:84%
And actually aesthetics,
the sense of beauty,

00:06:00.120 --> 00:06:02.530 align:middle line:84%
is part of the divine
as I now see it.

00:06:02.530 --> 00:06:03.330 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:06:03.330 --> 00:06:04.450 align:middle line:90%
You became an atheist.

00:06:04.450 --> 00:06:05.866 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: I
became an atheist.

00:06:05.866 --> 00:06:08.490 align:middle line:84%
Then when I went to Cambridge
as an undergraduate,

00:06:08.490 --> 00:06:11.940 align:middle line:84%
I joined the main atheist
society, the Cambridge Humanist

00:06:11.940 --> 00:06:13.890 align:middle line:90%
Society.

00:06:13.890 --> 00:06:15.660 align:middle line:84%
The trouble is that
after a term or two,

00:06:15.660 --> 00:06:17.460 align:middle line:84%
I began to find it
all rather dull.

00:06:17.460 --> 00:06:21.720 align:middle line:84%
I mean, people were just sort
of told jokes against religion

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:25.140 align:middle line:84%
and made arguments against,
if Adam and Eve were

00:06:25.140 --> 00:06:29.320 align:middle line:84%
created by God, how come
they've got navels in paintings?

00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:31.210 align:middle line:90%
You know, that kind of thing.

00:06:31.210 --> 00:06:35.230 align:middle line:84%
Almost kind of schoolboy
level atheist arguments.

00:06:35.230 --> 00:06:40.840 align:middle line:84%
So it became not very
interesting to me.

00:06:40.840 --> 00:06:42.690 align:middle line:84%
And so I got interested
in philosophy.

00:06:42.690 --> 00:06:44.530 align:middle line:84%
I was looking for
a deeper meaning,

00:06:44.530 --> 00:06:48.250 align:middle line:84%
and I also started looking for
a deeper way of understanding

00:06:48.250 --> 00:06:51.640 align:middle line:84%
living organisms, because the
mechanistic theories seemed

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:52.565 align:middle line:90%
to me too limited.

00:06:52.565 --> 00:06:54.940 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Well, let's talk
about the philosophical part,

00:06:54.940 --> 00:06:56.260 align:middle line:90%
because you started--

00:06:56.260 --> 00:06:59.140 align:middle line:84%
you took a little dive
into Freud and Karl Marx

00:06:59.140 --> 00:07:00.060 align:middle line:90%
during this era.

00:07:00.060 --> 00:07:02.020 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Oh, well I
started off with the atheist

00:07:02.020 --> 00:07:02.820 align:middle line:90%
philosopher.

00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:04.180 align:middle line:10%
I mean, I read Freud.

00:07:04.180 --> 00:07:08.830 align:middle line:10%
And Freud reinforced
all my atheist views

00:07:08.830 --> 00:07:12.310 align:middle line:10%
because he saw religion
as just a projection of--

00:07:12.310 --> 00:07:14.930 align:middle line:10%
God's just a projection
of a father figure,

00:07:14.930 --> 00:07:18.430 align:middle line:10%
and these are just
basic needs built

00:07:18.430 --> 00:07:24.580 align:middle line:10%
into our psyche to provide
us with comfort and illusory

00:07:24.580 --> 00:07:26.450 align:middle line:10%
support.

00:07:26.450 --> 00:07:30.970 align:middle line:84%
So he was unrelenting in
his dismissal of religion.

00:07:30.970 --> 00:07:33.580 align:middle line:10%
And Marx, who had to
view that it was just

00:07:33.580 --> 00:07:38.350 align:middle line:10%
a conspiracy of priests
provide the opium of the people

00:07:38.350 --> 00:07:42.440 align:middle line:10%
to stop people
revolting and achieving

00:07:42.440 --> 00:07:45.760 align:middle line:10%
the dictatorship
of the proletariat.

00:07:45.760 --> 00:07:49.010 align:middle line:90%
I quite liked all that.

00:07:49.010 --> 00:07:51.280 align:middle line:84%
But again, it began
to seem rather

00:07:51.280 --> 00:07:52.604 align:middle line:90%
unsatisfying after a while.

00:07:52.604 --> 00:07:54.270 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Well, I
would think it would.

00:07:54.270 --> 00:07:56.996 align:middle line:84%
Let's go on to
Sir Julian Huxley.

00:07:56.996 --> 00:07:58.370 align:middle line:84%
That was kind of
an interesting--

00:07:58.370 --> 00:08:00.120 align:middle line:84%
he was just a little
mention in your book,

00:08:00.120 --> 00:08:02.320 align:middle line:84%
but it really takes you
down a rabbit hole that

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:04.960 align:middle line:84%
starts looking frighteningly
like some of what's

00:08:04.960 --> 00:08:07.780 align:middle line:84%
happening today, even
almost crossing over

00:08:07.780 --> 00:08:10.520 align:middle line:90%
into the transhuman movement.

00:08:10.520 --> 00:08:13.730 align:middle line:10%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, Sir Julian
Huxley was the leading secular

00:08:13.730 --> 00:08:16.400 align:middle line:10%
humanist of his era.

00:08:16.400 --> 00:08:20.630 align:middle line:10%
And he came gave a talk to the
Cambridge Humanist Association.

00:08:20.630 --> 00:08:21.440 align:middle line:90%
So I went to it.

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:24.440 align:middle line:84%
He was a famous
evolutionary biologist.

00:08:24.440 --> 00:08:27.700 align:middle line:90%
I was doing biology.

00:08:27.700 --> 00:08:31.930 align:middle line:84%
And he gave this talk about the
need to enhance the human race.

00:08:31.930 --> 00:08:34.929 align:middle line:84%
Basically, the lower
classes are out-breeding

00:08:34.929 --> 00:08:36.730 align:middle line:90%
the intelligent classes.

00:08:36.730 --> 00:08:41.320 align:middle line:84%
So this would be very bad news
for the future of humanity

00:08:41.320 --> 00:08:44.680 align:middle line:84%
because the poor breed
like rabbits and the rich

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:46.370 align:middle line:90%
don't have enough children.

00:08:46.370 --> 00:08:50.380 align:middle line:84%
So what we need is to
uplift the human race

00:08:50.380 --> 00:08:53.790 align:middle line:84%
through selective breeding
and what we need--

00:08:53.790 --> 00:08:57.280 align:middle line:84%
the simple way of doing that
is through sperm donors.

00:08:57.280 --> 00:08:59.950 align:middle line:84%
And the ideal sperm
donor should be

00:08:59.950 --> 00:09:03.610 align:middle line:84%
a man of distinguished
scientific background, who's

00:09:03.610 --> 00:09:06.490 align:middle line:84%
achieved eminence
in public life,

00:09:06.490 --> 00:09:10.660 align:middle line:84%
who's preferably an
eminent scientist,

00:09:10.660 --> 00:09:16.050 align:middle line:84%
and who is widely recognized and
esteemed for his achievements.

00:09:16.050 --> 00:09:18.540 align:middle line:84%
And it turned out the
perfect sperm donor

00:09:18.540 --> 00:09:19.840 align:middle line:90%
was Sir Julian Huxley himself.

00:09:19.840 --> 00:09:21.048 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: His very own self.

00:09:21.048 --> 00:09:22.222 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes.

00:09:22.222 --> 00:09:24.370 align:middle line:84%
And at first, I
wasn't sure whether he

00:09:24.370 --> 00:09:26.042 align:middle line:90%
was serious about this.

00:09:26.042 --> 00:09:27.750 align:middle line:84%
But funnily enough,
just a few years ago,

00:09:27.750 --> 00:09:30.250 align:middle line:84%
only three or four
years ago, I was

00:09:30.250 --> 00:09:32.630 align:middle line:84%
friendly with his
son, Francis Huxley,

00:09:32.630 --> 00:09:35.770 align:middle line:90%
who died a little while ago.

00:09:35.770 --> 00:09:38.890 align:middle line:84%
And Francis started
getting emails and letters

00:09:38.890 --> 00:09:41.110 align:middle line:84%
from people saying that
they'd been doing research

00:09:41.110 --> 00:09:43.300 align:middle line:84%
on their ancestry
and they had reason

00:09:43.300 --> 00:09:48.610 align:middle line:84%
to believe that their father was
his father, Sir Julian Huxley,

00:09:48.610 --> 00:09:52.540 align:middle line:84%
and would he spit into a
test tube for DNA tests

00:09:52.540 --> 00:09:53.612 align:middle line:90%
so they could find out--

00:09:53.612 --> 00:09:54.570 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Interesting.

00:09:54.570 --> 00:09:56.260 align:middle line:90%
How many of these showed up?

00:09:56.260 --> 00:09:59.940 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, the
thing is, quite a lot.

00:09:59.940 --> 00:10:02.060 align:middle line:84%
And Francis was
appalled by this.

00:10:02.060 --> 00:10:03.730 align:middle line:84%
He didn't get on
well with his father.

00:10:03.730 --> 00:10:05.271 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: I just
find this so funny.

00:10:05.271 --> 00:10:07.916 align:middle line:90%
I'm sorry.

00:10:07.916 --> 00:10:10.500 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, he
was so-- so I said to him,

00:10:10.500 --> 00:10:11.997 align:middle line:84%
what do you do
with these letters?

00:10:11.997 --> 00:10:14.080 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: I mean, do you
call them step-siblings?

00:10:14.080 --> 00:10:15.280 align:middle line:84%
What do you call
them at that point?

00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:17.530 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, they would
be half brothers and sisters.

00:10:17.530 --> 00:10:18.100 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Exactly.

00:10:18.100 --> 00:10:18.320 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:10:18.320 --> 00:10:18.550 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:10:18.550 --> 00:10:19.630 align:middle line:90%
Half brothers and sisters.

00:10:19.630 --> 00:10:20.050 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:10:20.050 --> 00:10:21.010 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes.

00:10:21.010 --> 00:10:23.550 align:middle line:90%
Maybe dozens of them.

00:10:23.550 --> 00:10:24.670 align:middle line:90%
And all of a sudden--

00:10:24.670 --> 00:10:26.830 align:middle line:90%
he was over 90 at the time.

00:10:26.830 --> 00:10:30.400 align:middle line:84%
The last thing he wanted was
all these people showing up

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:35.460 align:middle line:84%
who claim to have been half
brothers and half sisters.

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:37.580 align:middle line:84%
So I said, what do you
do with these requests?

00:10:37.580 --> 00:10:40.570 align:middle line:84%
Have you spat into a test
tube for the DNA test?

00:10:40.570 --> 00:10:41.930 align:middle line:90%
He said, of course not.

00:10:41.930 --> 00:10:44.020 align:middle line:84%
I said, what do you
do with the requests?

00:10:44.020 --> 00:10:46.700 align:middle line:84%
I just throw the letters into
the wastepaper basket, he said.

00:10:46.700 --> 00:10:47.860 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Oh my God.

00:10:47.860 --> 00:10:52.750 align:middle line:84%
Well, that experiment
ended poorly for him,

00:10:52.750 --> 00:10:54.550 align:middle line:84%
but I suppose his
father would have

00:10:54.550 --> 00:10:58.960 align:middle line:84%
been proud to have had so many
essential clones of himself

00:10:58.960 --> 00:11:00.071 align:middle line:90%
out there.

00:11:00.071 --> 00:11:02.320 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: With enough
scientific curiosity to find

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:03.930 align:middle line:90%
out who their father was, yes.

00:11:03.930 --> 00:11:05.186 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:11:05.186 --> 00:11:06.680 align:middle line:90%
Interesting.

00:11:06.680 --> 00:11:07.480 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:07.480 --> 00:11:09.520 align:middle line:84%
So now let's talk
about your transition

00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:14.199 align:middle line:84%
away from this phase
of your education.

00:11:14.199 --> 00:11:16.740 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, I think the
first thing that happened was

00:11:16.740 --> 00:11:20.250 align:middle line:84%
that I began to find the machine
theory of life inadequate

00:11:20.250 --> 00:11:23.520 align:middle line:84%
for understanding
living organisms.

00:11:23.520 --> 00:11:26.220 align:middle line:10%
And I then discovered a
holistic approach to science

00:11:26.220 --> 00:11:31.080 align:middle line:10%
through reading the works of
the German poet Goethe, who

00:11:31.080 --> 00:11:35.940 align:middle line:10%
in the beginning of the
19th century, around 1800,

00:11:35.940 --> 00:11:39.930 align:middle line:10%
was trying to find a more
holistic approach to nature,

00:11:39.930 --> 00:11:42.180 align:middle line:10%
where you could base
your understanding

00:11:42.180 --> 00:11:45.150 align:middle line:10%
not just on breaking
things down into bits,

00:11:45.150 --> 00:11:50.580 align:middle line:10%
but seeing them as a whole
and literally seeing things.

00:11:50.580 --> 00:11:53.280 align:middle line:84%
One of the things he did was
looked at plants in detail

00:11:53.280 --> 00:11:56.760 align:middle line:84%
and found that you could
find transitional forms

00:11:56.760 --> 00:12:00.870 align:middle line:84%
between leaves and sepals and
sepals and petals and petals

00:12:00.870 --> 00:12:02.220 align:middle line:90%
and stamens.

00:12:02.220 --> 00:12:04.620 align:middle line:84%
And he had the idea
that these were

00:12:04.620 --> 00:12:09.540 align:middle line:84%
all morphing of an underlying
leaf type structure that

00:12:09.540 --> 00:12:12.450 align:middle line:84%
could change into
these other organs

00:12:12.450 --> 00:12:15.900 align:middle line:84%
and that you could actually
see by looking at them how

00:12:15.900 --> 00:12:18.450 align:middle line:90%
one form changed into another.

00:12:18.450 --> 00:12:21.270 align:middle line:84%
And that was looking at
forms and understanding forms

00:12:21.270 --> 00:12:25.530 align:middle line:84%
by direct experience, rather
than grinding everything up

00:12:25.530 --> 00:12:27.840 align:middle line:84%
and analyzing the
chemicals inside it,

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:31.470 align:middle line:90%
which was the usual approach.

00:12:31.470 --> 00:12:34.560 align:middle line:84%
So that pointed me towards
a more holistic way

00:12:34.560 --> 00:12:36.780 align:middle line:90%
of seeing things.

00:12:36.780 --> 00:12:40.160 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't want to go
on doing science to--

00:12:40.160 --> 00:12:41.900 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I did very
well at Cambridge.

00:12:41.900 --> 00:12:43.030 align:middle line:90%
I got a double first.

00:12:43.030 --> 00:12:44.600 align:middle line:90%
I got college prizes.

00:12:44.600 --> 00:12:47.280 align:middle line:90%
I got university botany prize.

00:12:47.280 --> 00:12:49.850 align:middle line:90%
You know, I was the--

00:12:49.850 --> 00:12:52.910 align:middle line:84%
scientific researchers
wanted me to work with them,

00:12:52.910 --> 00:12:55.160 align:middle line:84%
but I didn't want to
do a PhD straightaway.

00:12:55.160 --> 00:12:56.450 align:middle line:90%
I wanted to sort of--

00:12:56.450 --> 00:12:59.920 align:middle line:84%
is this what I
really want to do?

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:00.930 align:middle line:90%
So I was lucky.

00:13:00.930 --> 00:13:03.990 align:middle line:84%
I got a fellowship at Harvard,
called a Frank Knox Fellowship,

00:13:03.990 --> 00:13:07.290 align:middle line:84%
which gave me a blissfully
free year at Harvard, where

00:13:07.290 --> 00:13:09.570 align:middle line:84%
I studied history and
philosophy of science

00:13:09.570 --> 00:13:12.340 align:middle line:90%
to get a big picture.

00:13:12.340 --> 00:13:14.030 align:middle line:90%
And this was a long time ago.

00:13:14.030 --> 00:13:16.600 align:middle line:10%
This was soon after Thomas
Kuhn's famous book had just

00:13:16.600 --> 00:13:19.960 align:middle line:10%
been published, "The Structure
of Scientific Revolutions",

00:13:19.960 --> 00:13:24.080 align:middle line:10%
where he introduced the idea of
paradigms and paradigm shifts.

00:13:24.080 --> 00:13:28.280 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's now a cliche, but
he published the book in 1962.

00:13:28.280 --> 00:13:30.550 align:middle line:90%
I was at Harvard in 1963.

00:13:30.550 --> 00:13:32.470 align:middle line:90%
So this was the latest thing.

00:13:32.470 --> 00:13:35.220 align:middle line:84%
Only people in philosophy
of science knew about it.

00:13:35.220 --> 00:13:37.330 align:middle line:84%
It hadn't reached
popular culture.

00:13:37.330 --> 00:13:41.140 align:middle line:84%
And I was blown
away by this book

00:13:41.140 --> 00:13:44.410 align:middle line:84%
because what it showed was
that the way science is thought

00:13:44.410 --> 00:13:47.710 align:middle line:84%
of at any given time
is not the truth, which

00:13:47.710 --> 00:13:50.420 align:middle line:84%
is what I'd been led
to believe it was,

00:13:50.420 --> 00:13:51.910 align:middle line:90%
it's a model of reality.

00:13:51.910 --> 00:13:53.155 align:middle line:90%
And these models can change.

00:13:53.155 --> 00:13:56.200 align:middle line:84%
And the history of science
has plenty of examples

00:13:56.200 --> 00:13:58.810 align:middle line:90%
of these models changing.

00:13:58.810 --> 00:14:02.530 align:middle line:84%
So I suddenly thought, wow,
well, this machine theory

00:14:02.530 --> 00:14:04.870 align:middle line:84%
of life that
dominates everything

00:14:04.870 --> 00:14:08.230 align:middle line:84%
isn't the only way of looking at
it, and the model could change.

00:14:08.230 --> 00:14:10.900 align:middle line:84%
A new kind of biology
might be possible.

00:14:10.900 --> 00:14:13.930 align:middle line:84%
This gave me tremendous
sense of hope for the future,

00:14:13.930 --> 00:14:16.240 align:middle line:84%
that science didn't
have to remain locked

00:14:16.240 --> 00:14:20.260 align:middle line:84%
into this atheistic,
materialist, narrow,

00:14:20.260 --> 00:14:22.450 align:middle line:84%
it's all just the
molecules, the mind's

00:14:22.450 --> 00:14:24.490 align:middle line:90%
just the brain point of view.

00:14:24.490 --> 00:14:27.690 align:middle line:84%
It could be
interestingly broader.

00:14:27.690 --> 00:14:29.860 align:middle line:84%
But I didn't see
how to go there.

00:14:29.860 --> 00:14:32.282 align:middle line:84%
I didn't know how to
move in that direction.

00:14:32.282 --> 00:14:34.240 align:middle line:84%
But at least it gave me
the hope it was worth--

00:14:34.240 --> 00:14:34.930 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Well,
it's interesting

00:14:34.930 --> 00:14:36.696 align:middle line:84%
because you're dealing
with institutions.

00:14:36.696 --> 00:14:38.695 align:middle line:84%
At that time you were
dealing with institutions.

00:14:38.695 --> 00:14:40.894 align:middle line:84%
So you're talking about
funding and tenure

00:14:40.894 --> 00:14:42.310 align:middle line:84%
and all these sorts
of things that

00:14:42.310 --> 00:14:43.610 align:middle line:90%
are threatened by new ideas.

00:14:43.610 --> 00:14:44.410 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes.

00:14:44.410 --> 00:14:48.670 align:middle line:84%
Well, at that stage, in
my particular position,

00:14:48.670 --> 00:14:51.940 align:middle line:84%
the only way forward to remain
in institutional science

00:14:51.940 --> 00:14:55.030 align:middle line:84%
was to do a PhD, which
I went back to Cambridge

00:14:55.030 --> 00:14:57.160 align:middle line:90%
and did on plant development.

00:14:57.160 --> 00:15:01.420 align:middle line:84%
And I worked an area where
I could think holistically.

00:15:01.420 --> 00:15:03.430 align:middle line:84%
I worked on plants
because I'd had

00:15:03.430 --> 00:15:05.920 align:middle line:84%
enough experience of working
on animals to realize

00:15:05.920 --> 00:15:08.680 align:middle line:84%
that a scientific career
working on animals

00:15:08.680 --> 00:15:12.280 align:middle line:84%
involves killing animals
on an industrial scale,

00:15:12.280 --> 00:15:14.740 align:middle line:84%
and I didn't want to spend
my career killing animals.

00:15:14.740 --> 00:15:17.980 align:middle line:84%
I went into biology because
I loved animals and kept them

00:15:17.980 --> 00:15:22.000 align:middle line:84%
and had pets I was
really fond of.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:23.286 align:middle line:90%
So plants seemed to me--

00:15:23.286 --> 00:15:24.910 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it does
involve killing plants,

00:15:24.910 --> 00:15:26.560 align:middle line:84%
but I didn't feel
too bad about that.

00:15:26.560 --> 00:15:28.815 align:middle line:84%
I mean, even
vegetarians eat lettuce

00:15:28.815 --> 00:15:31.160 align:middle line:84%
and that's a living
leaf and so on.

00:15:31.160 --> 00:15:31.960 align:middle line:90%
Anyway.

00:15:31.960 --> 00:15:34.390 align:middle line:84%
I felt OK about doing
research on plants.

00:15:34.390 --> 00:15:38.200 align:middle line:84%
I had a great time in
Cambridge doing this.

00:15:38.200 --> 00:15:41.140 align:middle line:10%
And while I was a graduate
student at Cambridge,

00:15:41.140 --> 00:15:44.560 align:middle line:10%
I met a very eccentric group
of philosophers, called

00:15:44.560 --> 00:15:48.070 align:middle line:10%
the Epiphany Philosophers,
who had some very high powered

00:15:48.070 --> 00:15:50.230 align:middle line:10%
philosophers in it-- the
professor of philosophy

00:15:50.230 --> 00:15:53.050 align:middle line:10%
at Cambridge, a woman
called Dorothy Emmet

00:15:53.050 --> 00:15:55.330 align:middle line:10%
who was professor of
philosophy at Manchester, who'd

00:15:55.330 --> 00:16:01.330 align:middle line:10%
studied with Whitehead, the
great holistic philosopher,

00:16:01.330 --> 00:16:05.800 align:middle line:10%
quantum physicists, some
Buddhists, some people

00:16:05.800 --> 00:16:08.200 align:middle line:10%
into tai chi.

00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:10.570 align:middle line:84%
And this group was
basically Anglican--

00:16:10.570 --> 00:16:14.860 align:middle line:84%
contained some Quakers as well,
but also Buddhists and holistic

00:16:14.860 --> 00:16:16.640 align:middle line:90%
medicine and so on--

00:16:16.640 --> 00:16:20.590 align:middle line:84%
and was exploring a way
forward for science.

00:16:20.590 --> 00:16:23.620 align:middle line:84%
And everyone in the group
was influenced by Kuhn's idea

00:16:23.620 --> 00:16:25.210 align:middle line:90%
of a paradigm shift.

00:16:25.210 --> 00:16:26.825 align:middle line:84%
What would be the
next paradigm shift?

00:16:26.825 --> 00:16:28.660 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: How fortunate
you found this group.

00:16:28.660 --> 00:16:29.460 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes.

00:16:29.460 --> 00:16:32.380 align:middle line:84%
I was incredibly fortunate to
find because nobody else was

00:16:32.380 --> 00:16:34.820 align:middle line:90%
talking about these things.

00:16:34.820 --> 00:16:36.660 align:middle line:90%
And so I was in this group.

00:16:36.660 --> 00:16:39.650 align:middle line:90%
And we had four retreats a year.

00:16:39.650 --> 00:16:42.020 align:middle line:84%
We lived in a windmill
on the coast of Norfolk,

00:16:42.020 --> 00:16:45.850 align:middle line:84%
a place called Burnham Overy
Staithe, as a community.

00:16:45.850 --> 00:16:48.750 align:middle line:84%
So for a week we all
lived as a community.

00:16:48.750 --> 00:16:50.150 align:middle line:90%
We ate together.

00:16:50.150 --> 00:16:53.900 align:middle line:84%
We had a rota to cook
and wash up and things.

00:16:53.900 --> 00:16:57.530 align:middle line:84%
Every morning we had a
seminar on some topic.

00:16:57.530 --> 00:17:00.260 align:middle line:10%
Sometimes people
like Arthur Koestler

00:17:00.260 --> 00:17:03.110 align:middle line:10%
came for these seminars.

00:17:03.110 --> 00:17:07.339 align:middle line:10%
Sometimes holistically minded
writers and philosophers.

00:17:07.339 --> 00:17:09.440 align:middle line:90%
Mostly it was among ourselves.

00:17:09.440 --> 00:17:11.480 align:middle line:84%
The implications
of quantum theory.

00:17:11.480 --> 00:17:14.630 align:middle line:84%
The nature of consciousness,
the possibility

00:17:14.630 --> 00:17:18.200 align:middle line:84%
of a holistic biology,
the limitations of the DNA

00:17:18.200 --> 00:17:20.930 align:middle line:90%
approach to life, and so on.

00:17:20.930 --> 00:17:23.126 align:middle line:84%
This was amazing
to be part of it.

00:17:23.126 --> 00:17:24.500 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: It
sounds like heaven.

00:17:24.500 --> 00:17:26.060 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: It was.

00:17:26.060 --> 00:17:27.230 align:middle line:90%
It was hard hitting, though.

00:17:27.230 --> 00:17:32.090 align:middle line:84%
I mean, these discussions
were very, very hard hitting.

00:17:32.090 --> 00:17:35.840 align:middle line:84%
There was no nonsense tolerated,
and people were often reduced

00:17:35.840 --> 00:17:38.080 align:middle line:90%
to tears in these discussions.

00:17:38.080 --> 00:17:42.590 align:middle line:84%
But because it was a
religious type community,

00:17:42.590 --> 00:17:44.300 align:middle line:84%
I wasn't really into
that side of it,

00:17:44.300 --> 00:17:48.590 align:middle line:84%
but we had every morning,
before the day began,

00:17:48.590 --> 00:17:51.440 align:middle line:84%
we did the Anglican
matins service

00:17:51.440 --> 00:17:54.740 align:middle line:84%
and in the evening
the evensong service,

00:17:54.740 --> 00:17:58.220 align:middle line:84%
chanting, in
plainsong, the psalms.

00:17:58.220 --> 00:17:59.990 align:middle line:84%
And each day began
with something

00:17:59.990 --> 00:18:02.040 align:middle line:90%
called the Chapter of Faults.

00:18:02.040 --> 00:18:05.180 align:middle line:84%
And we were all in these
white robes in the top floor

00:18:05.180 --> 00:18:07.760 align:middle line:90%
of the windmill in a circle.

00:18:07.760 --> 00:18:09.740 align:middle line:84%
And one by one, starting
with the oldest,

00:18:09.740 --> 00:18:12.740 align:middle line:84%
we had to go round and
confess to the group things

00:18:12.740 --> 00:18:15.770 align:middle line:84%
that we'd done that
would have upset people.

00:18:15.770 --> 00:18:19.530 align:middle line:84%
It wasn't like deep,
existential faults.

00:18:19.530 --> 00:18:21.772 align:middle line:84%
It was not doing your
share of the washing

00:18:21.772 --> 00:18:22.730 align:middle line:90%
up, that kind of thing.

00:18:22.730 --> 00:18:25.188 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: So ideally within
the community in the last week

00:18:25.188 --> 00:18:27.316 align:middle line:84%
or 24 hours, not your
deeply held secrets.

00:18:27.316 --> 00:18:28.440 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: No, nothing--

00:18:28.440 --> 00:18:31.170 align:middle line:84%
no, no, no, not
deeply held secrets.

00:18:31.170 --> 00:18:32.620 align:middle line:84%
Just things that
might have upset

00:18:32.620 --> 00:18:34.720 align:middle line:90%
other people in the community.

00:18:34.720 --> 00:18:37.710 align:middle line:84%
And first you confessed these
things, then you had to say,

00:18:37.710 --> 00:18:40.220 align:middle line:84%
if anyone has anything
else to remind me of,

00:18:40.220 --> 00:18:42.450 align:middle line:90%
I'd be grateful to be told.

00:18:42.450 --> 00:18:45.690 align:middle line:84%
And because this was a
somewhat argumentative group,

00:18:45.690 --> 00:18:48.920 align:middle line:84%
quite often people did say
things that had upset them.

00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:52.010 align:middle line:84%
And what this did
was cleared the air,

00:18:52.010 --> 00:18:54.430 align:middle line:84%
and then we all sang
together after this.

00:18:54.430 --> 00:18:58.080 align:middle line:84%
And it sort of meant that
this rather cantankerous group

00:18:58.080 --> 00:19:01.980 align:middle line:84%
of people, very argumentative,
could come together every day

00:19:01.980 --> 00:19:04.410 align:middle line:90%
and start each day afresh.

00:19:04.410 --> 00:19:07.920 align:middle line:84%
And if you did have
any grudge or upset,

00:19:07.920 --> 00:19:09.390 align:middle line:90%
you could bring it out then.

00:19:09.390 --> 00:19:11.160 align:middle line:84%
So this actually
worked very well.

00:19:11.160 --> 00:19:13.260 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:19:13.260 --> 00:19:17.580 align:middle line:84%
In this period of time, what
really came to the fore for you

00:19:17.580 --> 00:19:18.804 align:middle line:90%
as a young man?

00:19:18.804 --> 00:19:20.220 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well,
at this stage,

00:19:20.220 --> 00:19:22.530 align:middle line:84%
the spiritual side
wasn't the main thing.

00:19:22.530 --> 00:19:27.540 align:middle line:84%
What came to the fore for me
was the idea that consciousness

00:19:27.540 --> 00:19:31.230 align:middle line:84%
wasn't explained by
science, that quantum theory

00:19:31.230 --> 00:19:35.150 align:middle line:84%
had completely broken with the
old mechanical view of nature,

00:19:35.150 --> 00:19:39.360 align:middle line:84%
and determinism
was part of nature.

00:19:39.360 --> 00:19:42.520 align:middle line:84%
There was an involvement
of consciousness in science

00:19:42.520 --> 00:19:43.320 align:middle line:90%
itself.

00:19:43.320 --> 00:19:46.740 align:middle line:84%
You can't have observations
without an observer.

00:19:46.740 --> 00:19:49.650 align:middle line:84%
The mind is involved
in producing science.

00:19:49.650 --> 00:19:53.890 align:middle line:84%
And our mental models are
what underlies science.

00:19:53.890 --> 00:19:56.610 align:middle line:84%
It's not reality itself
that we're seeing.

00:19:56.610 --> 00:20:01.220 align:middle line:84%
We're seeing our models of
reality, and those change.

00:20:01.220 --> 00:20:02.930 align:middle line:84%
And this encouraged
me to think there

00:20:02.930 --> 00:20:05.510 align:middle line:84%
could be a more holistic
view in biology,

00:20:05.510 --> 00:20:08.720 align:middle line:84%
which would also include a
more holistic view of medicine.

00:20:08.720 --> 00:20:12.150 align:middle line:84%
Instead of medicine just
being about surgery and drugs,

00:20:12.150 --> 00:20:18.580 align:middle line:84%
it could include consciousness,
expectation, belief, and what's

00:20:18.580 --> 00:20:20.360 align:middle line:90%
now called the placebo effect.

00:20:20.360 --> 00:20:22.850 align:middle line:84%
All these things were
important ingredients.

00:20:22.850 --> 00:20:24.180 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:20:24.180 --> 00:20:25.906 align:middle line:84%
Now this is a bit
of a non-sequitur,

00:20:25.906 --> 00:20:28.280 align:middle line:84%
but as I'm listening to you
and thinking of Goethe and so

00:20:28.280 --> 00:20:30.680 align:middle line:84%
forth, my mind wanders
quite naturally

00:20:30.680 --> 00:20:33.470 align:middle line:84%
to Rudolf Steiner and a lot
of what he brought forward

00:20:33.470 --> 00:20:35.360 align:middle line:90%
by way of a system.

00:20:35.360 --> 00:20:37.250 align:middle line:84%
Any quick comments you
might have before we

00:20:37.250 --> 00:20:39.910 align:middle line:90%
start moving on to India?

00:20:39.910 --> 00:20:44.350 align:middle line:10%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, Steiner
was a follower of Goethe,

00:20:44.350 --> 00:20:48.550 align:middle line:10%
and many of the things I found
interesting in Goethe were also

00:20:48.550 --> 00:20:51.110 align:middle line:10%
things that Steiner
found interesting.

00:20:51.110 --> 00:20:52.920 align:middle line:84%
I didn't know about
Steiner at that stage,

00:20:52.920 --> 00:20:54.290 align:middle line:90%
or only vaguely heard of him.

00:20:54.290 --> 00:20:55.090 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:20:55.090 --> 00:20:57.820 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: So I didn't get
these ideas through Steiner.

00:20:57.820 --> 00:20:59.630 align:middle line:84%
I got them through
Goethe himself.

00:20:59.630 --> 00:21:00.430 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:21:00.430 --> 00:21:02.450 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: I
later discovered,

00:21:02.450 --> 00:21:05.680 align:middle line:84%
not in that phase as a
graduate student at Cambridge,

00:21:05.680 --> 00:21:08.380 align:middle line:84%
but later, people said, did
you know there's this whole

00:21:08.380 --> 00:21:12.130 align:middle line:84%
movement following Steiner, and
they look at plants in a way

00:21:12.130 --> 00:21:14.800 align:middle line:84%
that is holistic
following Goethe?

00:21:14.800 --> 00:21:16.540 align:middle line:84%
And they even have
schools where they

00:21:16.540 --> 00:21:19.100 align:middle line:84%
teach science in a
much more holistic way,

00:21:19.100 --> 00:21:21.300 align:middle line:90%
Waldorf or Steiner schools.

00:21:21.300 --> 00:21:23.301 align:middle line:84%
I didn't know anything
about that at that stage.

00:21:23.301 --> 00:21:24.100 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:21:24.100 --> 00:21:25.220 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:21:25.220 --> 00:21:26.020 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:21:26.020 --> 00:21:28.780 align:middle line:84%
Let's take your life
forward to India,

00:21:28.780 --> 00:21:30.640 align:middle line:84%
where you spent a
number of years.

00:21:30.640 --> 00:21:33.970 align:middle line:84%
And then where you met a
Sufi mystic and the thing

00:21:33.970 --> 00:21:35.470 align:middle line:84%
he said to you
that really started

00:21:35.470 --> 00:21:37.700 align:middle line:90%
shifting things for you.

00:21:37.700 --> 00:21:39.450 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, I
went to India twice.

00:21:39.450 --> 00:21:44.450 align:middle line:84%
In 1968 I got a
Royal Society grant

00:21:44.450 --> 00:21:47.060 align:middle line:84%
to study tropical
rainforest plants

00:21:47.060 --> 00:21:51.310 align:middle line:84%
at the University of Malaya
in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.

00:21:51.310 --> 00:21:53.840 align:middle line:84%
And they gave me one of
those old style airline

00:21:53.840 --> 00:21:56.270 align:middle line:84%
tickets where you could break
the journey as often as you

00:21:56.270 --> 00:21:57.070 align:middle line:90%
liked.

00:21:57.070 --> 00:21:59.690 align:middle line:84%
So I decided, well, instead
of just flying over India,

00:21:59.690 --> 00:22:03.350 align:middle line:84%
I'll get off in India and
just taste a bit of India

00:22:03.350 --> 00:22:04.700 align:middle line:90%
on the way.

00:22:04.700 --> 00:22:06.770 align:middle line:84%
I'd only been there two
or three days in Delhi

00:22:06.770 --> 00:22:10.430 align:middle line:84%
when I ran into, by chance, the
one person I knew in India, who

00:22:10.430 --> 00:22:13.100 align:middle line:84%
was a graduate student
friend from Cambridge, who

00:22:13.100 --> 00:22:16.730 align:middle line:84%
was an anthropologist
living with a family

00:22:16.730 --> 00:22:19.010 align:middle line:84%
in a remote village
in the Himalayas.

00:22:19.010 --> 00:22:20.510 align:middle line:84%
And he said, would
you like to come?

00:22:20.510 --> 00:22:21.509 align:middle line:90%
I'm going back tomorrow.

00:22:21.509 --> 00:22:25.072 align:middle line:84%
Would you like to come
to my village with me?

00:22:25.072 --> 00:22:26.330 align:middle line:90%
So I said, yes.

00:22:26.330 --> 00:22:29.650 align:middle line:84%
So I went to the British Airways
office, changed my ticket.

00:22:29.650 --> 00:22:33.500 align:middle line:84%
And I was plunged
into rural Indian life

00:22:33.500 --> 00:22:37.020 align:middle line:84%
in a village which
didn't have electricity.

00:22:37.020 --> 00:22:40.280 align:middle line:90%
And of course, no radio or TV.

00:22:40.280 --> 00:22:43.820 align:middle line:84%
And I was living in a
kind of medieval world.

00:22:43.820 --> 00:22:45.260 align:middle line:90%
It was fascinating.

00:22:45.260 --> 00:22:47.150 align:middle line:84%
And here were people
of great faith.

00:22:47.150 --> 00:22:49.090 align:middle line:90%
I met this guru.

00:22:49.090 --> 00:22:50.690 align:middle line:84%
We went for a walk
along the valley,

00:22:50.690 --> 00:22:54.740 align:middle line:84%
and I saw this orange clad
figure sitting in a cave.

00:22:54.740 --> 00:22:57.960 align:middle line:84%
And I said to my friend,
Johnny, who's that?

00:22:57.960 --> 00:22:59.820 align:middle line:84%
And he said, oh, he's
the local holy man.

00:22:59.820 --> 00:23:02.680 align:middle line:84%
I hadn't heard of
sadhus and holy men.

00:23:02.680 --> 00:23:05.170 align:middle line:84%
I'd only been in India
three or four days.

00:23:05.170 --> 00:23:08.350 align:middle line:84%
And there I was in the
heart of rural India.

00:23:08.350 --> 00:23:12.470 align:middle line:84%
And the sadhu beckoned us,
and we sat down in the cave.

00:23:12.470 --> 00:23:14.590 align:middle line:84%
And then he offered
me-- he'd got this clay

00:23:14.590 --> 00:23:16.910 align:middle line:90%
pipe, smoke coming out.

00:23:16.910 --> 00:23:18.310 align:middle line:90%
I didn't know what it was.

00:23:18.310 --> 00:23:21.700 align:middle line:84%
And he said, would you like to
try some of Shiva's holy plant?

00:23:21.700 --> 00:23:23.110 align:middle line:90%
So I said, well, why not.

00:23:23.110 --> 00:23:24.460 align:middle line:90%
Here I am in India.

00:23:24.460 --> 00:23:25.900 align:middle line:90%
Have a few puffs of this.

00:23:25.900 --> 00:23:28.450 align:middle line:84%
And it was an incredibly
strong cannabis thing.

00:23:28.450 --> 00:23:32.340 align:middle line:90%
I'd never had cannabis before.

00:23:32.340 --> 00:23:37.720 align:middle line:84%
And he started with a prayer
for the Enlightenment of the God

00:23:37.720 --> 00:23:38.550 align:middle line:90%
on the smoke.

00:23:38.550 --> 00:23:41.050 align:middle line:84%
So it was a kind of
spiritual practice.

00:23:41.050 --> 00:23:43.820 align:middle line:84%
It wasn't just smoking
a joint at a party.

00:23:43.820 --> 00:23:45.740 align:middle line:90%
It was completely different.

00:23:45.740 --> 00:23:47.680 align:middle line:90%
And I felt completely different.

00:23:47.680 --> 00:23:50.860 align:middle line:84%
When I walked out of the
cave into the sunlight,

00:23:50.860 --> 00:23:51.985 align:middle line:90%
there were the Himalayas.

00:23:51.985 --> 00:23:57.430 align:middle line:84%
There were these green-- here
was the green hills, the river.

00:23:57.430 --> 00:23:59.920 align:middle line:84%
I was in a state of bliss
that I'd never known before.

00:23:59.920 --> 00:24:01.520 align:middle line:90%
I though, this is incredible.

00:24:01.520 --> 00:24:04.870 align:middle line:84%
I felt really home,
really connected,

00:24:04.870 --> 00:24:09.440 align:middle line:84%
and as if a vast new world
was opening up for me.

00:24:09.440 --> 00:24:11.830 align:middle line:84%
And so I spent another two
or three months in India,

00:24:11.830 --> 00:24:14.580 align:middle line:84%
and I was very, very
impressed by it.

00:24:14.580 --> 00:24:18.420 align:middle line:90%
A whole civilisation based on--

00:24:18.420 --> 00:24:21.950 align:middle line:84%
everyone there had a kind
of spiritual dimension.

00:24:21.950 --> 00:24:23.700 align:middle line:90%
Then I got to Sri Lanka.

00:24:23.700 --> 00:24:25.340 align:middle line:84%
And I visited a
Buddhist monastery

00:24:25.340 --> 00:24:26.650 align:middle line:90%
and talked to some monks.

00:24:26.650 --> 00:24:29.330 align:middle line:84%
And they told me
about meditation.

00:24:29.330 --> 00:24:34.880 align:middle line:84%
Then I finally got to Malaysia,
and I had a marvelous time

00:24:34.880 --> 00:24:37.520 align:middle line:84%
studying rainforest
plants and being embedded

00:24:37.520 --> 00:24:40.280 align:middle line:90%
in this very exotic culture.

00:24:40.280 --> 00:24:43.640 align:middle line:84%
At that time, the
lowland rainforest jungle

00:24:43.640 --> 00:24:46.160 align:middle line:84%
came up within 10
miles of Kuala Lumpur.

00:24:46.160 --> 00:24:50.180 align:middle line:84%
You could be in primal
rainforest within half an hour

00:24:50.180 --> 00:24:51.320 align:middle line:90%
from the university.

00:24:51.320 --> 00:24:53.120 align:middle line:84%
Now, of course, that's
all been cleared

00:24:53.120 --> 00:24:55.820 align:middle line:84%
and development and
so on has taken over.

00:24:55.820 --> 00:25:01.400 align:middle line:84%
But this was a complete eye
opener for me-- biologically,

00:25:01.400 --> 00:25:04.490 align:middle line:84%
to be in the middle of
a rainforest, tropical

00:25:04.490 --> 00:25:07.700 align:middle line:84%
environment; culturally,
to be exposed

00:25:07.700 --> 00:25:10.430 align:middle line:84%
to Hinduism, Buddhism
in Sri Lanka,

00:25:10.430 --> 00:25:13.130 align:middle line:84%
and then in Malaysia,
Islam, where most people are

00:25:13.130 --> 00:25:15.885 align:middle line:90%
Muslim, and Chinese.

00:25:15.885 --> 00:25:18.200 align:middle line:84%
There were many Chinese
there so we came

00:25:18.200 --> 00:25:21.080 align:middle line:90%
across Taoism and Confucianism.

00:25:21.080 --> 00:25:23.690 align:middle line:84%
And I met tribal people
because they worked with us

00:25:23.690 --> 00:25:26.060 align:middle line:90%
on our botanical expeditions.

00:25:26.060 --> 00:25:29.810 align:middle line:84%
So this was a tremendously
mind opening experience,

00:25:29.810 --> 00:25:34.390 align:middle line:84%
followed by traveling in
Thailand and Cambodia and Laos.

00:25:34.390 --> 00:25:37.270 align:middle line:84%
And this was before they got
engulfed in the Vietnam War.

00:25:37.270 --> 00:25:38.980 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Right.

00:25:38.980 --> 00:25:40.730 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: So I
went back to Cambridge.

00:25:40.730 --> 00:25:43.910 align:middle line:84%
I had several more years there
doing research on plants.

00:25:43.910 --> 00:25:46.230 align:middle line:84%
But I then came to a point
where I had to decide,

00:25:46.230 --> 00:25:49.850 align:middle line:84%
do I want to go down a
regular academic track,

00:25:49.850 --> 00:25:52.630 align:middle line:84%
leading to being a professor
and all that kind of thing,

00:25:52.630 --> 00:25:56.040 align:middle line:84%
which I could have done,
or do something different?

00:25:56.040 --> 00:25:59.050 align:middle line:84%
And I felt so drawn
to India and I

00:25:59.050 --> 00:26:02.320 align:middle line:84%
felt so drawn to
working holistically

00:26:02.320 --> 00:26:06.160 align:middle line:84%
with plants that
an opportunity came

00:26:06.160 --> 00:26:08.350 align:middle line:84%
to work at a new
international institute

00:26:08.350 --> 00:26:11.050 align:middle line:84%
starting in India for
agricultural research,

00:26:11.050 --> 00:26:15.700 align:middle line:84%
called Icrisat, where I got
a job as the principal plant

00:26:15.700 --> 00:26:18.040 align:middle line:90%
physiologist.

00:26:18.040 --> 00:26:22.330 align:middle line:84%
I then had, from then on,
about seven years in India,

00:26:22.330 --> 00:26:27.190 align:middle line:84%
where I was working in the
fields on crop improvement,

00:26:27.190 --> 00:26:30.160 align:middle line:84%
doing useful work with
Indian colleagues,

00:26:30.160 --> 00:26:34.000 align:middle line:84%
mainly, but international
scientists as well.

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:38.510 align:middle line:84%
Immersed in this totally
fascinating culture.

00:26:38.510 --> 00:26:41.670 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: I have to say, just
a quick interjection here.

00:26:41.670 --> 00:26:45.340 align:middle line:84%
I spent a little time in India
and I flew back into Heathrow.

00:26:45.340 --> 00:26:47.890 align:middle line:84%
But when I flew back
in after experiencing

00:26:47.890 --> 00:26:53.200 align:middle line:84%
all the flavor and lushness and
sensuality and color and spices

00:26:53.200 --> 00:26:57.700 align:middle line:84%
and flew back into a world where
the men were all wearing gray,

00:26:57.700 --> 00:27:00.460 align:middle line:84%
gray, black, or navy blue,
and the women weren't

00:27:00.460 --> 00:27:04.030 align:middle line:84%
a lot more colorful, it was
one of those real shocks

00:27:04.030 --> 00:27:07.210 align:middle line:84%
as to what has happened
to us in Western culture.

00:27:07.210 --> 00:27:08.210 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, yes.

00:27:08.210 --> 00:27:09.020 align:middle line:90%
Well, I felt that.

00:27:09.020 --> 00:27:12.350 align:middle line:84%
I felt here's this amazingly
exotic, colorful world, which

00:27:12.350 --> 00:27:16.340 align:middle line:84%
is informed by a
sense of the spirit,

00:27:16.340 --> 00:27:18.980 align:middle line:84%
with amazing
traditions, cultures,

00:27:18.980 --> 00:27:24.770 align:middle line:84%
astonishing art, amazing
music, wonderful smells.

00:27:24.770 --> 00:27:26.837 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it's just marvelous.

00:27:26.837 --> 00:27:29.420 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: I can understand why
you went back for seven years.

00:27:29.420 --> 00:27:30.220 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes.

00:27:30.220 --> 00:27:31.220 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:27:31.220 --> 00:27:33.810 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: And I had
to job I loved doing,

00:27:33.810 --> 00:27:36.110 align:middle line:84%
real science that
could be useful.

00:27:36.110 --> 00:27:39.020 align:middle line:84%
By that stage I'd come up,
while I was at Cambridge,

00:27:39.020 --> 00:27:41.330 align:middle line:84%
with my idea about
morphogenetic fields

00:27:41.330 --> 00:27:44.310 align:middle line:84%
and morphic resonance,
memory in nature,

00:27:44.310 --> 00:27:48.260 align:middle line:84%
which was a very
heretical idea in science.

00:27:48.260 --> 00:27:51.360 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't feel I could
publish it until I'd

00:27:51.360 --> 00:27:52.540 align:middle line:90%
thought about it a lot more.

00:27:52.540 --> 00:27:55.080 align:middle line:84%
I knew it would be
very controversial.

00:27:55.080 --> 00:27:57.740 align:middle line:84%
So in India, working
on practical problems,

00:27:57.740 --> 00:28:03.560 align:middle line:84%
was a way of stepping back,
continuing to think about this.

00:28:03.560 --> 00:28:06.410 align:middle line:84%
Still doing science
but not having

00:28:06.410 --> 00:28:10.640 align:middle line:84%
to confront a kind
of clash of cultures

00:28:10.640 --> 00:28:12.640 align:middle line:84%
when I wasn't ready
to do that, when

00:28:12.640 --> 00:28:14.240 align:middle line:90%
I hadn't thought it through.

00:28:14.240 --> 00:28:15.800 align:middle line:84%
So in my spare
time I was thinking

00:28:15.800 --> 00:28:19.010 align:middle line:84%
about morphogenetic
fields, form shaping

00:28:19.010 --> 00:28:22.260 align:middle line:84%
fields, morphic resonance,
the memory in nature,

00:28:22.260 --> 00:28:25.464 align:middle line:84%
inheritance through
morphic resonance,

00:28:25.464 --> 00:28:26.505 align:middle line:90%
as well as through genes.

00:28:26.505 --> 00:28:29.200 align:middle line:90%


00:28:29.200 --> 00:28:31.930 align:middle line:84%
And then in India, I was
also, at the same time,

00:28:31.930 --> 00:28:34.450 align:middle line:84%
by then I'd taken up
transcendental meditation,

00:28:34.450 --> 00:28:37.210 align:middle line:84%
because I wanted to
explore consciousness.

00:28:37.210 --> 00:28:39.070 align:middle line:84%
Having gone through
a psychedelic phase

00:28:39.070 --> 00:28:41.140 align:middle line:84%
at Cambridge, which
shocked me out

00:28:41.140 --> 00:28:44.620 align:middle line:84%
of my complacency about the
mind being just the brain

00:28:44.620 --> 00:28:47.380 align:middle line:84%
and there were dimensions
of consciousness

00:28:47.380 --> 00:28:50.600 align:middle line:84%
no one had ever told me
about it in any tradition.

00:28:50.600 --> 00:28:52.600 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I hadn't
heard about this

00:28:52.600 --> 00:28:54.410 align:middle line:90%
in regular Christian tradition.

00:28:54.410 --> 00:28:57.490 align:middle line:84%
I hadn't heard about this
in the scientific tradition.

00:28:57.490 --> 00:29:03.090 align:middle line:10%
The only guides were people
like Aldous Huxley, who'd had--

00:29:03.090 --> 00:29:08.527 align:middle line:10%
his books on masculine and
the spiritual dimensions

00:29:08.527 --> 00:29:09.610 align:middle line:10%
of psychedelic experience.

00:29:09.610 --> 00:29:15.130 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And I suppose some
of the old Catholic mystics--

00:29:15.130 --> 00:29:18.170 align:middle line:90%
Eckhart, Hildegard von Bingen--

00:29:18.170 --> 00:29:22.120 align:middle line:84%
that had these experiences
and people still

00:29:22.120 --> 00:29:25.170 align:middle line:84%
try to guess whether or not
they were plant induced or not.

00:29:25.170 --> 00:29:27.970 align:middle line:84%
But other than that, there
was nothing in religion

00:29:27.970 --> 00:29:32.304 align:middle line:84%
that led us to understand
these dimensions of experience.

00:29:32.304 --> 00:29:33.470 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, exactly.

00:29:33.470 --> 00:29:36.130 align:middle line:84%
And in any case, at that
stage I was still more

00:29:36.130 --> 00:29:37.990 align:middle line:84%
or less atheistic,
and I didn't know

00:29:37.990 --> 00:29:40.060 align:middle line:84%
about the Christian
mystical tradition.

00:29:40.060 --> 00:29:43.580 align:middle line:84%
No one had ever
told me about it.

00:29:43.580 --> 00:29:45.790 align:middle line:84%
So I took up
transcendental meditation

00:29:45.790 --> 00:29:48.640 align:middle line:84%
because I wanted to explore
consciousness without drugs.

00:29:48.640 --> 00:29:52.620 align:middle line:84%
And I found it a very
helpful practice.

00:29:52.620 --> 00:29:54.322 align:middle line:84%
And the way it
was put across was

00:29:54.322 --> 00:29:55.780 align:middle line:84%
you don't need to
believe anything.

00:29:55.780 --> 00:29:57.780 align:middle line:84%
Just try it and
see what happens.

00:29:57.780 --> 00:29:58.700 align:middle line:90%
That was fine.

00:29:58.700 --> 00:30:00.490 align:middle line:84%
And I liked the
experimental approach.

00:30:00.490 --> 00:30:03.190 align:middle line:90%


00:30:03.190 --> 00:30:06.540 align:middle line:84%
And I also went to visit
Hindu temples and ashrams

00:30:06.540 --> 00:30:10.350 align:middle line:84%
and had got interested in
Hindu philosophy, which

00:30:10.350 --> 00:30:12.780 align:middle line:84%
has consciousness is
primary and sees this

00:30:12.780 --> 00:30:14.960 align:middle line:90%
as working through nature.

00:30:14.960 --> 00:30:17.400 align:middle line:84%
And I loved the fact they
had all these sacred trees

00:30:17.400 --> 00:30:19.770 align:middle line:90%
and animals and things.

00:30:19.770 --> 00:30:22.620 align:middle line:84%
There was a sense that
life wasn't just machinery.

00:30:22.620 --> 00:30:25.160 align:middle line:90%


00:30:25.160 --> 00:30:27.770 align:middle line:84%
At that stage, when I
was living in Hyderabad,

00:30:27.770 --> 00:30:33.050 align:middle line:84%
I was learning Urdu, because
that was the main lingua

00:30:33.050 --> 00:30:35.840 align:middle line:90%
franca of Hyderabad.

00:30:35.840 --> 00:30:40.180 align:middle line:84%
And I was very friendly
with a Muslim family who

00:30:40.180 --> 00:30:41.580 align:middle line:90%
I got on terribly well with.

00:30:41.580 --> 00:30:43.790 align:middle line:84%
And the grandfather
of that family,

00:30:43.790 --> 00:30:49.230 align:middle line:84%
a friend, his grandfather
was a Sufi teacher.

00:30:49.230 --> 00:30:51.870 align:middle line:84%
And he had a big
influence on me.

00:30:51.870 --> 00:30:58.110 align:middle line:84%
He was called [INAUDIBLE],,
and he spoke English.

00:30:58.110 --> 00:31:00.390 align:middle line:10%
He wore wonderful brocade robes.

00:31:00.390 --> 00:31:02.790 align:middle line:10%
He was very aesthetic.

00:31:02.790 --> 00:31:04.050 align:middle line:90%
He had perfumes.

00:31:04.050 --> 00:31:06.630 align:middle line:84%
And men in that
culture wear perfumes.

00:31:06.630 --> 00:31:08.370 align:middle line:84%
And when they get
together they're

00:31:08.370 --> 00:31:10.980 align:middle line:84%
wearing these marvelous
robes, and they're

00:31:10.980 --> 00:31:13.620 align:middle line:84%
smelling each other's
perfumes and stuff.

00:31:13.620 --> 00:31:17.200 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I hadn't come across
anything like that before.

00:31:17.200 --> 00:31:18.900 align:middle line:90%
And these are religious people.

00:31:18.900 --> 00:31:23.160 align:middle line:84%
So pleasure was, in their view
of the world, given by God.

00:31:23.160 --> 00:31:26.940 align:middle line:84%
It wasn't sinful or bad to
have things that were beautiful

00:31:26.940 --> 00:31:30.480 align:middle line:90%
or enjoy the pleasures of life.

00:31:30.480 --> 00:31:32.130 align:middle line:84%
They saw them as
gifts of God, and they

00:31:32.130 --> 00:31:33.030 align:middle line:90%
were grateful for them.

00:31:33.030 --> 00:31:34.571 align:middle line:84%
And I thought this
was much healthier

00:31:34.571 --> 00:31:39.990 align:middle line:84%
than the more puritanical
attitudes I was used to.

00:31:39.990 --> 00:31:42.490 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, he gave me a
Sufi form of meditation,

00:31:42.490 --> 00:31:44.850 align:middle line:90%
which I did for a year or so.

00:31:44.850 --> 00:31:47.370 align:middle line:84%
And I found that
really helpful too.

00:31:47.370 --> 00:31:51.480 align:middle line:84%
And I felt a connection
with the Islamic world

00:31:51.480 --> 00:31:52.575 align:middle line:90%
which I hadn't had before.

00:31:52.575 --> 00:31:55.170 align:middle line:90%


00:31:55.170 --> 00:31:58.950 align:middle line:84%
But then as I continued
my exploration,

00:31:58.950 --> 00:32:01.390 align:middle line:84%
this new thought
crossed my mind.

00:32:01.390 --> 00:32:03.570 align:middle line:90%
What about Christianity?

00:32:03.570 --> 00:32:06.950 align:middle line:84%
The one thing I had
not considered--

00:32:06.950 --> 00:32:08.920 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Your
very original roots.

00:32:08.920 --> 00:32:09.720 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes.

00:32:09.720 --> 00:32:10.890 align:middle line:90%
My original roots.

00:32:10.890 --> 00:32:13.180 align:middle line:84%
I later discovered this
is a very common factor

00:32:13.180 --> 00:32:14.790 align:middle line:90%
in our whole society today.

00:32:14.790 --> 00:32:18.300 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's what I
call the ABC principle.

00:32:18.300 --> 00:32:20.670 align:middle line:90%
Anything But Christian.

00:32:20.670 --> 00:32:22.280 align:middle line:90%
Buddhism Lite is fine.

00:32:22.280 --> 00:32:28.110 align:middle line:84%
A bit of a Native American
shamanism, Peruvian drumming,

00:32:28.110 --> 00:32:29.790 align:middle line:90%
as long as it's not Christian.

00:32:29.790 --> 00:32:34.830 align:middle line:84%
Anyway I was in the ABC
mentality at the time.

00:32:34.830 --> 00:32:36.750 align:middle line:84%
And then I started
trying to reconnect

00:32:36.750 --> 00:32:39.270 align:middle line:84%
with the Christian
tradition, and I found it

00:32:39.270 --> 00:32:42.960 align:middle line:84%
really helpful to feel
in harmony with my roots

00:32:42.960 --> 00:32:45.660 align:middle line:84%
and getting more into
contact with my ancestors

00:32:45.660 --> 00:32:47.930 align:middle line:84%
and the tradition
from which I'd come.

00:32:47.930 --> 00:32:51.720 align:middle line:84%
But I found that that
was still rather limited,

00:32:51.720 --> 00:32:55.830 align:middle line:84%
and it didn't take into account
the great philosophical depths

00:32:55.830 --> 00:33:00.610 align:middle line:84%
of Hinduism or insights into
consciousness of Buddhism.

00:33:00.610 --> 00:33:03.630 align:middle line:84%
I just went to regular
Anglican church services.

00:33:03.630 --> 00:33:06.270 align:middle line:84%
And I found I loved the
singing, I loved the music,

00:33:06.270 --> 00:33:11.260 align:middle line:84%
I was used to it, but it didn't
have this mystical dimension.

00:33:11.260 --> 00:33:13.480 align:middle line:10%
And at that stage, a
friend introduced me

00:33:13.480 --> 00:33:17.410 align:middle line:10%
to an English
Benedictine monk called

00:33:17.410 --> 00:33:21.160 align:middle line:10%
Father Bede Griffiths, who lived
in an ashram in South India.

00:33:21.160 --> 00:33:22.920 align:middle line:10%
I went to visit him.

00:33:22.920 --> 00:33:26.710 align:middle line:84%
And this was, for me, the
moment of great revelation.

00:33:26.710 --> 00:33:28.905 align:middle line:84%
He didn't reject all
these Hindu and Buddhists

00:33:28.905 --> 00:33:30.120 align:middle line:90%
and he accepted them.

00:33:30.120 --> 00:33:32.410 align:middle line:84%
He thought they were great
insights into the nature

00:33:32.410 --> 00:33:34.910 align:middle line:90%
of ultimate reality.

00:33:34.910 --> 00:33:37.860 align:middle line:84%
But he also was very
aware of Meister Eckhart

00:33:37.860 --> 00:33:40.270 align:middle line:84%
and the whole Christian
mystical tradition,

00:33:40.270 --> 00:33:43.720 align:middle line:84%
which he told me about and
I'd never heard about before,

00:33:43.720 --> 00:33:45.520 align:middle line:84%
and had produced a
kind of integration

00:33:45.520 --> 00:33:52.320 align:middle line:84%
of these traditions, which was
just the perfect thing for me.

00:33:52.320 --> 00:33:56.150 align:middle line:84%
So when I came to write my
book on morphic resonance

00:33:56.150 --> 00:33:58.291 align:middle line:84%
a couple of years
later, he said, well,

00:33:58.291 --> 00:34:00.290 align:middle line:84%
if you want to stay in
India to write your book,

00:34:00.290 --> 00:34:03.250 align:middle line:84%
just come and live in the
ashram as long as you like.

00:34:03.250 --> 00:34:04.050 align:middle line:90%
So I did.

00:34:04.050 --> 00:34:08.360 align:middle line:84%
And so I spent two years in
this ashram writing my book,

00:34:08.360 --> 00:34:10.644 align:middle line:84%
"A New Science of
Life," my first book.

00:34:10.644 --> 00:34:11.810 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: That's wonderful.

00:34:11.810 --> 00:34:14.114 align:middle line:10%
And you had contact
with him the whole time?

00:34:14.114 --> 00:34:15.530 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: I
saw him every day.

00:34:15.530 --> 00:34:15.780 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:34:15.780 --> 00:34:15.929 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Every day.

00:34:15.929 --> 00:34:16.909 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: I mean, it
was a small community.

00:34:16.909 --> 00:34:18.075 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: What a privilege.

00:34:18.075 --> 00:34:20.510 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Hindu ashrams
in India were overwhelmed with

00:34:20.510 --> 00:34:21.310 align:middle line:90%
Western visitors.

00:34:21.310 --> 00:34:23.760 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the Sai Baba
ashram, for example,

00:34:23.760 --> 00:34:26.130 align:middle line:84%
would have like 1,000
Westerners at any given time.

00:34:26.130 --> 00:34:27.754 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Well, The Beatles
had already done their thing.

00:34:27.754 --> 00:34:27.830 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:34:27.830 --> 00:34:28.469 align:middle line:90%
Right

00:34:28.469 --> 00:34:28.729 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes.

00:34:28.729 --> 00:34:29.529 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: So yes.

00:34:29.529 --> 00:34:33.400 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: So the Hindu
ashrams were all crowded with

00:34:33.400 --> 00:34:34.489 align:middle line:90%
spiritual tourists.

00:34:34.489 --> 00:34:37.679 align:middle line:84%
Bus loads of Italians
arriving every day and things.

00:34:37.679 --> 00:34:40.460 align:middle line:84%
But a Christian ashram,
because most people

00:34:40.460 --> 00:34:42.949 align:middle line:84%
worked on the anything but
Christian principle, most

00:34:42.949 --> 00:34:44.929 align:middle line:84%
Westerners, the last
thing they thought of--

00:34:44.929 --> 00:34:45.409 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Was peaceful.

00:34:45.409 --> 00:34:47.570 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: --was going
to a Christian ashram.

00:34:47.570 --> 00:34:49.880 align:middle line:84%
Most of the people there
were Indian Christians.

00:34:49.880 --> 00:34:54.365 align:middle line:84%
It was actually ironically more
Indian than the Indian ashrams,

00:34:54.365 --> 00:34:55.359 align:middle line:90%
the Hindu ashrams--

00:34:55.359 --> 00:34:56.317 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Interesting.

00:34:56.317 --> 00:34:59.270 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: --and smaller
and much more peaceful.

00:34:59.270 --> 00:35:02.690 align:middle line:84%
So at any given time there'd
only about 30 or 40 people

00:35:02.690 --> 00:35:03.710 align:middle line:90%
there.

00:35:03.710 --> 00:35:06.390 align:middle line:90%
And I saw Father Bede every day.

00:35:06.390 --> 00:35:11.530 align:middle line:84%
And as I wrote my book, I
wrote it with a fountain pen

00:35:11.530 --> 00:35:13.290 align:middle line:90%
in exercise books.

00:35:13.290 --> 00:35:15.920 align:middle line:84%
And he read it
chapter by chapter,

00:35:15.920 --> 00:35:18.760 align:middle line:84%
and we had long discussions
about everything.

00:35:18.760 --> 00:35:20.630 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: What a
lovely collaboration.

00:35:20.630 --> 00:35:21.449 align:middle line:90%
That's beautiful.

00:35:21.449 --> 00:35:22.740 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: It was fantastic.

00:35:22.740 --> 00:35:23.760 align:middle line:84%
Although he didn't
know much science,

00:35:23.760 --> 00:35:25.210 align:middle line:90%
he knew a lot about philosophy.

00:35:25.210 --> 00:35:26.010 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Right.

00:35:26.010 --> 00:35:29.400 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: And when I had
to explain the science to me,

00:35:29.400 --> 00:35:32.660 align:middle line:84%
he'd say, Rupert, what
is a magnetic field,

00:35:32.660 --> 00:35:33.830 align:middle line:90%
and how does it work?

00:35:33.830 --> 00:35:35.840 align:middle line:84%
Then I had to give
these kind of tutorials

00:35:35.840 --> 00:35:39.800 align:middle line:84%
to this great sage on
elementary science.

00:35:39.800 --> 00:35:43.310 align:middle line:84%
Very, very bright but he hadn't
had a scientific background.

00:35:43.310 --> 00:35:45.410 align:middle line:84%
And this was wonderfully
good practice

00:35:45.410 --> 00:35:48.290 align:middle line:84%
in explaining scientific
ideas to someone who

00:35:48.290 --> 00:35:50.000 align:middle line:90%
was clever, but not scientific.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:50.900 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Right.

00:35:50.900 --> 00:35:52.316 align:middle line:84%
Well, I've said
off camera, you've

00:35:52.316 --> 00:35:53.960 align:middle line:84%
had to me what
sounds to me to be

00:35:53.960 --> 00:35:55.940 align:middle line:90%
such a beautiful, charmed life.

00:35:55.940 --> 00:35:58.190 align:middle line:84%
And you've been able to
experience and indulge

00:35:58.190 --> 00:35:59.810 align:middle line:90%
in all of the things.

00:35:59.810 --> 00:36:02.040 align:middle line:84%
Anywhere your curiosity
could take you,

00:36:02.040 --> 00:36:05.030 align:middle line:84%
you've had just these exemplary
experiences, such as what

00:36:05.030 --> 00:36:06.540 align:middle line:90%
you just spoke about.

00:36:06.540 --> 00:36:09.980 align:middle line:84%
And now what I'd like to do
is after that, after you began

00:36:09.980 --> 00:36:12.200 align:middle line:84%
expanding your own
base of awareness,

00:36:12.200 --> 00:36:14.090 align:middle line:84%
after you went
back the ABC thing,

00:36:14.090 --> 00:36:17.840 align:middle line:84%
went back and started
also expressing yourself

00:36:17.840 --> 00:36:22.572 align:middle line:84%
through song and such through
your Anglican tradition,

00:36:22.572 --> 00:36:24.530 align:middle line:84%
you've moved forward to
a time where now you're

00:36:24.530 --> 00:36:27.380 align:middle line:84%
blending the two in
this newest book, right?

00:36:27.380 --> 00:36:31.490 align:middle line:84%
And I think what's fascinating
about it is because we're still

00:36:31.490 --> 00:36:32.890 align:middle line:90%
in the ABC mode, big time.

00:36:32.890 --> 00:36:33.690 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes.

00:36:33.690 --> 00:36:35.148 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And
let's do some stats.

00:36:35.148 --> 00:36:40.970 align:middle line:84%
We'll go from all this lush
imagery in India to some stats.

00:36:40.970 --> 00:36:44.930 align:middle line:84%
And you talk about in your
book, today only 5% of Brits

00:36:44.930 --> 00:36:46.592 align:middle line:90%
attend church regularly.

00:36:46.592 --> 00:36:48.050 align:middle line:84%
Well, you go through
every village,

00:36:48.050 --> 00:36:51.560 align:middle line:84%
you have these wonderful
little churches and chapels,

00:36:51.560 --> 00:36:53.090 align:middle line:84%
and you still have
the bells ringing

00:36:53.090 --> 00:36:54.530 align:middle line:90%
but nobody's showing up.

00:36:54.530 --> 00:36:55.610 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:36:55.610 --> 00:36:57.510 align:middle line:90%
And that's for church itself.

00:36:57.510 --> 00:36:58.310 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes.

00:36:58.310 --> 00:37:03.050 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And the stats are
18% in formerly Catholic Irish

00:37:03.050 --> 00:37:08.270 align:middle line:84%
Republic, 5% in France, and I
don't know that our viewership

00:37:08.270 --> 00:37:11.600 align:middle line:84%
would be totally shocked to
find one of the higher rates

00:37:11.600 --> 00:37:14.537 align:middle line:84%
of Christian attendance
in church is America.

00:37:14.537 --> 00:37:16.620 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Much higher
than anywhere in Europe,

00:37:16.620 --> 00:37:17.480 align:middle line:90%
except Poland.

00:37:17.480 --> 00:37:18.280 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:37:18.280 --> 00:37:23.850 align:middle line:84%
I mean, Europe is a
post-Christian block of nations

00:37:23.850 --> 00:37:24.650 align:middle line:90%
now.

00:37:24.650 --> 00:37:26.030 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:37:26.030 --> 00:37:30.500 align:middle line:84%
And so with atheism and
science as the masters,

00:37:30.500 --> 00:37:35.450 align:middle line:84%
as the, essentially,
rulers philosophically,

00:37:35.450 --> 00:37:38.630 align:middle line:84%
there are some shifts that
have occurred in society

00:37:38.630 --> 00:37:40.210 align:middle line:90%
that are significant.

00:37:40.210 --> 00:37:42.830 align:middle line:84%
And there are some things
that have been lost.

00:37:42.830 --> 00:37:44.330 align:middle line:84%
And it doesn't
matter whether it's

00:37:44.330 --> 00:37:47.180 align:middle line:84%
Christianity or any
religion, I mean,

00:37:47.180 --> 00:37:49.760 align:middle line:84%
really, it's the spiritual
principles we're talking about.

00:37:49.760 --> 00:37:52.970 align:middle line:84%
If they're not being employed
in the culture at large,

00:37:52.970 --> 00:37:55.550 align:middle line:84%
you have an issue of
ethics and morality

00:37:55.550 --> 00:37:57.810 align:middle line:84%
and such that
starts taking a hit.

00:37:57.810 --> 00:38:00.450 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about
that for a moment.

00:38:00.450 --> 00:38:04.020 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, I think
what's happened, basically,

00:38:04.020 --> 00:38:08.970 align:middle line:84%
is the ruling philosophy
of post-Christian Europe,

00:38:08.970 --> 00:38:13.080 align:middle line:84%
is the ruling philosophy
has become secular humanism.

00:38:13.080 --> 00:38:15.420 align:middle line:84%
And secular humanism
is quite interesting

00:38:15.420 --> 00:38:18.410 align:middle line:84%
because it is a kind
of religion in itself.

00:38:18.410 --> 00:38:22.380 align:middle line:84%
Although most secular humanists
would call themselves atheists,

00:38:22.380 --> 00:38:26.370 align:middle line:84%
they don't believe
in the Christian God,

00:38:26.370 --> 00:38:29.610 align:middle line:84%
but the structure of secular
humanism, and indeed,

00:38:29.610 --> 00:38:33.480 align:middle line:84%
its morality, is very
similar to Christianity.

00:38:33.480 --> 00:38:36.780 align:middle line:84%
Basically, what they've
done is got rid of God

00:38:36.780 --> 00:38:38.460 align:middle line:90%
and made humanity God.

00:38:38.460 --> 00:38:42.600 align:middle line:84%
So it's like Christianity
where humans become divine.

00:38:42.600 --> 00:38:45.210 align:middle line:84%
And that's why secular
humanism in some ways

00:38:45.210 --> 00:38:49.270 align:middle line:84%
is even more vigorous in its
assertions of human rights

00:38:49.270 --> 00:38:54.140 align:middle line:84%
and, say, opposition
to the death penalty,

00:38:54.140 --> 00:38:57.810 align:middle line:84%
including everyone,
previously rejected groups

00:38:57.810 --> 00:39:00.460 align:middle line:84%
like gays and
transsexuals, et cetera.

00:39:00.460 --> 00:39:02.880 align:middle line:84%
Everyone has to be included
because they're human.

00:39:02.880 --> 00:39:03.200 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:39:03.200 --> 00:39:04.000 align:middle line:90%
That's true.

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:04.980 align:middle line:90%
Very inclusive.

00:39:04.980 --> 00:39:08.960 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: It has
great strengths, I think.

00:39:08.960 --> 00:39:10.890 align:middle line:84%
I didn't see this
completely clearly

00:39:10.890 --> 00:39:14.640 align:middle line:84%
until I read recently Yuval
Noah Hararos book "Homo

00:39:14.640 --> 00:39:17.760 align:middle line:84%
Deus," which is a big
bestseller here in Britain.

00:39:17.760 --> 00:39:19.770 align:middle line:90%
Probably in America too.

00:39:19.770 --> 00:39:21.420 align:middle line:84%
He makes it very
clear that that is

