doing there is trying

00:48:13.050 --> 00:48:16.530 align:middle line:84%
to let go of thoughts
and your regular concerns

00:48:16.530 --> 00:48:18.600 align:middle line:84%
and your regular
involvements with the world

00:48:18.600 --> 00:48:21.060 align:middle line:84%
and detach yourself
from it to go

00:48:21.060 --> 00:48:24.030 align:middle line:84%
to the very ground of
consciousness itself,

00:48:24.030 --> 00:48:28.380 align:middle line:84%
which turns out to be
enormously relaxing, connecting,

00:48:28.380 --> 00:48:30.280 align:middle line:90%
and powerfully healthy.

00:48:30.280 --> 00:48:31.080 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Indeed.

00:48:31.080 --> 00:48:33.240 align:middle line:84%
And you can have incredible
breakthrough insights

00:48:33.240 --> 00:48:34.170 align:middle line:90%
from that place.

00:48:34.170 --> 00:48:34.480 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Exactly.

00:48:34.480 --> 00:48:36.813 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: When the mind is
completely still and relaxed

00:48:36.813 --> 00:48:38.340 align:middle line:90%
and unperturbed.

00:48:38.340 --> 00:48:39.360 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Exactly.

00:48:39.360 --> 00:48:40.650 align:middle line:90%
But it comes by itself.

00:48:40.650 --> 00:48:41.040 align:middle line:90%
You can't--

00:48:41.040 --> 00:48:41.440 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:48:41.440 --> 00:48:42.273 align:middle line:90%
You cannot force it.

00:48:42.273 --> 00:48:45.030 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: However hard
you try, you can't force it.

00:48:45.030 --> 00:48:47.640 align:middle line:84%
Now, petitionary prayer,
asking for things,

00:48:47.640 --> 00:48:49.900 align:middle line:84%
it works in exactly
the opposite direction.

00:48:49.900 --> 00:48:52.680 align:middle line:84%
That's like withdrawing from
the outer world coming in,

00:48:52.680 --> 00:48:54.410 align:middle line:90%
like breathing in.

00:48:54.410 --> 00:48:57.720 align:middle line:84%
In petitionary prayer, you
start by making a connection

00:48:57.720 --> 00:49:01.380 align:middle line:90%
with a spiritual realm or being.

00:49:01.380 --> 00:49:04.000 align:middle line:84%
Petitionary prayers
start with an invocation,

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:09.090 align:middle line:84%
"Our Father, who art in Heaven,"
"Hail Mary, full of grace,"

00:49:09.090 --> 00:49:12.990 align:middle line:90%
[HINDU] for a Hindu invocation.

00:49:12.990 --> 00:49:17.880 align:middle line:84%
You start by invoking the
being to which you're praying.

00:49:17.880 --> 00:49:20.400 align:middle line:84%
So you connect with
the spiritual realm,

00:49:20.400 --> 00:49:22.800 align:middle line:84%
and then you link it to
what you're concerned

00:49:22.800 --> 00:49:24.330 align:middle line:90%
about in the outer world.

00:49:24.330 --> 00:49:26.820 align:middle line:84%
Someone who's sick that
you're praying for.

00:49:26.820 --> 00:49:29.700 align:middle line:84%
Something you are frightened
of that you want help with.

00:49:29.700 --> 00:49:34.920 align:middle line:84%
Something that you want a
sense of purpose or meaning

00:49:34.920 --> 00:49:35.720 align:middle line:90%
in your life.

00:49:35.720 --> 00:49:38.130 align:middle line:84%
You want the grace to be
able to forgive somebody.

00:49:38.130 --> 00:49:42.870 align:middle line:84%
Whatever you are asking for, for
other people or for yourself,

00:49:42.870 --> 00:49:44.940 align:middle line:84%
is connecting the
spiritual realm

00:49:44.940 --> 00:49:46.980 align:middle line:84%
with the concerns of
your everyday life.

00:49:46.980 --> 00:49:48.570 align:middle line:84%
So it's like the
opposite direction.

00:49:48.570 --> 00:49:51.360 align:middle line:84%
It's from the spirit
outwards, and the other's

00:49:51.360 --> 00:49:52.831 align:middle line:90%
from outwards to the spirit.

00:49:52.831 --> 00:49:55.080 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And for you, the
balance of the two is what

00:49:55.080 --> 00:49:56.340 align:middle line:90%
works best?

00:49:56.340 --> 00:49:59.280 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes, because I
think just meditation, you see,

00:49:59.280 --> 00:50:02.710 align:middle line:84%
leaves unaddressed the
concerns of everyday life.

00:50:02.710 --> 00:50:03.510 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:50:03.510 --> 00:50:05.510 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Each of us,
by the end of the day,

00:50:05.510 --> 00:50:07.784 align:middle line:84%
I've got things that
I want to pray about,

00:50:07.784 --> 00:50:08.700 align:middle line:90%
about what's happened.

00:50:08.700 --> 00:50:10.900 align:middle line:84%
I want to give thanks for
things that have happened.

00:50:10.900 --> 00:50:12.974 align:middle line:84%
I want to pray for people
I know who are sick

00:50:12.974 --> 00:50:13.890 align:middle line:90%
or who are in trouble.

00:50:13.890 --> 00:50:14.220 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:50:14.220 --> 00:50:15.900 align:middle line:84%
And that's another big one
we're going to go to next,

00:50:15.900 --> 00:50:16.790 align:middle line:90%
is gratitude.

00:50:16.790 --> 00:50:19.123 align:middle line:84%
But before we do, I wanted
to say, you share in the book

00:50:19.123 --> 00:50:21.240 align:middle line:84%
that dozens of
members of parliament

00:50:21.240 --> 00:50:22.930 align:middle line:90%
have begun meditating.

00:50:22.930 --> 00:50:23.730 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes.

00:50:23.730 --> 00:50:24.609 align:middle line:90%
There's over 100.

00:50:24.609 --> 00:50:26.650 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: I think that's
absolutely fascinating.

00:50:26.650 --> 00:50:29.400 align:middle line:84%
I mean, if there were ever
a stressful, left-brained

00:50:29.400 --> 00:50:30.870 align:middle line:90%
environment.

00:50:30.870 --> 00:50:32.460 align:middle line:90%
And that's wonderful.

00:50:32.460 --> 00:50:34.590 align:middle line:90%
How was that spearheaded?

00:50:34.590 --> 00:50:37.540 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, there are
people who teach meditation who

00:50:37.540 --> 00:50:41.220 align:middle line:84%
hit on the idea of inviting
members of Parliament to go

00:50:41.220 --> 00:50:44.829 align:middle line:84%
to meditation courses or classes
in the houses of Parliament.

00:50:44.829 --> 00:50:45.870 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: That's lovely.

00:50:45.870 --> 00:50:48.328 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: And then having
a regular group meeting where

00:50:48.328 --> 00:50:50.380 align:middle line:84%
they can go and
meditate together.

00:50:50.380 --> 00:50:52.110 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Maybe they'll find
higher purpose in their work

00:50:52.110 --> 00:50:52.860 align:middle line:90%
that way too.

00:50:52.860 --> 00:50:53.610 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well,
they may well.

00:50:53.610 --> 00:50:55.560 align:middle line:84%
I mean, they'd
certainly find a relief

00:50:55.560 --> 00:50:57.750 align:middle line:84%
from the stress and
a kind of window

00:50:57.750 --> 00:51:01.100 align:middle line:90%
into a more calm state of being.

00:51:01.100 --> 00:51:01.900 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:51:01.900 --> 00:51:04.800 align:middle line:84%
A calm state of being where you
can make decisions in a clear

00:51:04.800 --> 00:51:06.000 align:middle line:90%
headed state too.

00:51:06.000 --> 00:51:06.270 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes.

00:51:06.270 --> 00:51:08.853 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And then, also, the
National Health Service here is

00:51:08.853 --> 00:51:10.360 align:middle line:90%
now recommending meditation.

00:51:10.360 --> 00:51:13.170 align:middle line:84%
Of course, it's going to
keep the budget intact

00:51:13.170 --> 00:51:15.354 align:middle line:84%
if you have people
remaining calm and healthy.

00:51:15.354 --> 00:51:16.520 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, exactly.

00:51:16.520 --> 00:51:19.700 align:middle line:84%
It's mainly recommended for
people with mild to moderate

00:51:19.700 --> 00:51:20.500 align:middle line:90%
depression.

00:51:20.500 --> 00:51:24.120 align:middle line:84%
And this is a huge problem here
as it is in the United States.

00:51:24.120 --> 00:51:25.780 align:middle line:90%
Depression is endemic.

00:51:25.780 --> 00:51:26.580 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:51:26.580 --> 00:51:29.080 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: And I don't think
it's surprising it's endemic

00:51:29.080 --> 00:51:31.960 align:middle line:84%
in a society where people
feel isolated and think

00:51:31.960 --> 00:51:35.040 align:middle line:84%
they're leading pointless
lives in a pointless world.

00:51:35.040 --> 00:51:39.640 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it's a modern disease.

00:51:39.640 --> 00:51:42.330 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out
that meditation can

00:51:42.330 --> 00:51:44.790 align:middle line:84%
be as effective, if not
more effective and certainly

00:51:44.790 --> 00:51:47.880 align:middle line:84%
cheaper, than
antidepressants like Prozac.

00:51:47.880 --> 00:51:48.690 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:51:48.690 --> 00:51:50.070 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: So this is now--

00:51:50.070 --> 00:51:51.930 align:middle line:84%
they actually did
clinical trials,

00:51:51.930 --> 00:51:54.870 align:middle line:84%
comparing meditation
with antidepressants,

00:51:54.870 --> 00:51:57.270 align:middle line:90%
to see which worked best.

00:51:57.270 --> 00:52:00.690 align:middle line:84%
And in many ways, the
meditation worked better.

00:52:00.690 --> 00:52:02.740 align:middle line:84%
And of course, has
fewer side effects.

00:52:02.740 --> 00:52:03.540 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:52:03.540 --> 00:52:04.530 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:52:04.530 --> 00:52:07.800 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about-- let's
move on to gratitude.

00:52:07.800 --> 00:52:10.980 align:middle line:84%
And one of the things
I love in the book

00:52:10.980 --> 00:52:12.930 align:middle line:84%
is you talk about,
let's start with some

00:52:12.930 --> 00:52:16.770 align:middle line:84%
of the really essential elements
of life, like the sun itself.

00:52:16.770 --> 00:52:18.960 align:middle line:84%
How many cultures, how
many people-- the Brits,

00:52:18.960 --> 00:52:22.020 align:middle line:90%
in particular, worship the sun.

00:52:22.020 --> 00:52:25.440 align:middle line:84%
And the notion of something
brilliant and life

00:52:25.440 --> 00:52:27.150 align:middle line:90%
giving and multi-dimensional.

00:52:27.150 --> 00:52:31.560 align:middle line:84%
So that's where we can begin
gratitude on a daily basis.

00:52:31.560 --> 00:52:35.235 align:middle line:84%
And from there, your
practice of gratitude.

00:52:35.235 --> 00:52:37.200 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, mine
has different levels.

00:52:37.200 --> 00:52:41.330 align:middle line:84%
I mean, part of
it is the simplest

00:52:41.330 --> 00:52:44.850 align:middle line:84%
and most straightforward form of
gratitude are for other people,

00:52:44.850 --> 00:52:48.180 align:middle line:84%
because we all depend
on other people.

00:52:48.180 --> 00:52:51.690 align:middle line:84%
And then as we move out from the
other people on whom we depend,

00:52:51.690 --> 00:52:55.890 align:middle line:84%
people who grow our
food, bring it to us,

00:52:55.890 --> 00:52:58.680 align:middle line:84%
help us in our lives--
doctors, dentists,

00:52:58.680 --> 00:53:03.270 align:middle line:84%
bus drivers, maintenance
engineers, teachers.

00:53:03.270 --> 00:53:07.260 align:middle line:84%
I mean, there's so many
people we depend on.

00:53:07.260 --> 00:53:08.070 align:middle line:90%
That's one level.

00:53:08.070 --> 00:53:09.960 align:middle line:84%
Then there's the
ecology that gives rise

00:53:09.960 --> 00:53:13.335 align:middle line:84%
to the food and our life and
the Earth, the whole Earth

00:53:13.335 --> 00:53:15.970 align:middle line:90%
on which all of us depend.

00:53:15.970 --> 00:53:18.230 align:middle line:84%
And I think if we
take it for granted,

00:53:18.230 --> 00:53:21.070 align:middle line:90%
then we run into real danger.

00:53:21.070 --> 00:53:23.170 align:middle line:84%
The ecological crisis
is based on just

00:53:23.170 --> 00:53:24.520 align:middle line:90%
taking the Earth for granted.

00:53:24.520 --> 00:53:25.320 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:53:25.320 --> 00:53:27.700 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: We take
but we don't give,

00:53:27.700 --> 00:53:30.250 align:middle line:90%
even don't give thanks.

00:53:30.250 --> 00:53:32.620 align:middle line:84%
But then the sun,
you see, the Earth

00:53:32.620 --> 00:53:35.950 align:middle line:84%
itself is part of a much larger
system, the solar system,

00:53:35.950 --> 00:53:37.440 align:middle line:90%
and that's part of the galaxy.

00:53:37.440 --> 00:53:43.750 align:middle line:84%
So I mean, the sun, if the
sun sends out a coronal mass

00:53:43.750 --> 00:53:45.520 align:middle line:84%
ejection pointed
towards the Earth,

00:53:45.520 --> 00:53:48.790 align:middle line:84%
it could take out all
our communication systems

00:53:48.790 --> 00:53:50.540 align:middle line:90%
in no time at all.

00:53:50.540 --> 00:53:55.860 align:middle line:84%
And so we take for
granted the sun.

00:53:55.860 --> 00:53:57.680 align:middle line:84%
And the sun is like
a living organism.

00:53:57.680 --> 00:53:59.990 align:middle line:90%
It has constant activity.

00:53:59.990 --> 00:54:02.140 align:middle line:84%
That's why NASA
has a space weather

00:54:02.140 --> 00:54:06.160 align:middle line:84%
forecast, because the sun's
activity affects life on Earth.

00:54:06.160 --> 00:54:09.210 align:middle line:84%
It's not just a standard
emitter like a light bulb or--

00:54:09.210 --> 00:54:10.010 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Exactly.

00:54:10.010 --> 00:54:11.350 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE:
--uniform radiation.

00:54:11.350 --> 00:54:13.849 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And it's always been
believed by ancient cultures

00:54:13.849 --> 00:54:19.720 align:middle line:84%
to have its own intelligence of
a vast multi-dimensional nature

00:54:19.720 --> 00:54:21.984 align:middle line:84%
that it's sharing
and perpetuating.

00:54:21.984 --> 00:54:23.150 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, exactly.

00:54:23.150 --> 00:54:25.060 align:middle line:90%
And I learned this--

00:54:25.060 --> 00:54:27.340 align:middle line:84%
well, I never learned it
from anyone in England.

00:54:27.340 --> 00:54:30.910 align:middle line:84%
But when I was in India,
when I learned yoga,

00:54:30.910 --> 00:54:34.170 align:middle line:84%
one of the things that I
learned was Surya Namaskar,

00:54:34.170 --> 00:54:35.660 align:middle line:90%
prostration to the sun.

00:54:35.660 --> 00:54:37.600 align:middle line:10%
It's a basic yoga exercise.

00:54:37.600 --> 00:54:40.860 align:middle line:10%
I've done it every day
for more than 40 years.

00:54:40.860 --> 00:54:42.820 align:middle line:10%
I did it this morning
when I got up.

00:54:42.820 --> 00:54:45.820 align:middle line:10%
And that's an
acknowledgement to the sun.

00:54:45.820 --> 00:54:48.590 align:middle line:10%
On one level, it's a
really good exercise.

00:54:48.590 --> 00:54:50.470 align:middle line:84%
Another level,
you're facing the sun

00:54:50.470 --> 00:54:53.740 align:middle line:84%
or facing a window where
the sunlight is coming in

00:54:53.740 --> 00:54:57.790 align:middle line:84%
and acknowledging the sun on
which all our lives depend.

00:54:57.790 --> 00:54:59.250 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:54:59.250 --> 00:55:01.590 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Another Hindu
practice is one of the most

00:55:01.590 --> 00:55:05.320 align:middle line:84%
common of all their mantras,
is the Gaia Tree Mantra,

00:55:05.320 --> 00:55:08.610 align:middle line:84%
which is a mantra which
asks the sun to illuminate

00:55:08.610 --> 00:55:12.310 align:middle line:84%
our meditation, the glorious
divine splendor of the sun

00:55:12.310 --> 00:55:13.620 align:middle line:90%
to illuminate our meditation.

00:55:13.620 --> 00:55:14.750 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes.

00:55:14.750 --> 00:55:16.334 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:55:16.334 --> 00:55:18.000 align:middle line:84%
And I'm really glad
you wrote about that

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:20.190 align:middle line:84%
because that's something
that's been fairly lost

00:55:20.190 --> 00:55:21.720 align:middle line:90%
in Western culture.

00:55:21.720 --> 00:55:25.440 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about beauty
for beauty's sake too.

00:55:25.440 --> 00:55:27.960 align:middle line:84%
This is something I
feel very strongly.

00:55:27.960 --> 00:55:31.502 align:middle line:84%
About our sense
of innate beauty,

00:55:31.502 --> 00:55:33.960 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't matter which of the
senses it's running through,

00:55:33.960 --> 00:55:39.780 align:middle line:84%
has been fairly well obscured
as a result of using devices.

00:55:39.780 --> 00:55:43.030 align:middle line:84%
We're not connected with the
sensual world as much anymore.

00:55:43.030 --> 00:55:45.370 align:middle line:84%
We've had so much fun
talking to this point.

00:55:45.370 --> 00:55:48.030 align:middle line:84%
So let's for a moment
just address the nature

00:55:48.030 --> 00:55:50.489 align:middle line:84%
the nature of beauty
itself for beauty's sake.

00:55:50.489 --> 00:55:52.530 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: I think when
we think about beauty,

00:55:52.530 --> 00:55:56.130 align:middle line:84%
the first idea that most people
have is it's just in our minds

00:55:56.130 --> 00:55:58.260 align:middle line:90%
and it's not really out there.

00:55:58.260 --> 00:55:59.340 align:middle line:90%
It's just in our minds.

00:55:59.340 --> 00:56:01.740 align:middle line:84%
But if you think
about it, it soon

00:56:01.740 --> 00:56:04.290 align:middle line:84%
becomes clear that it's
much more than that.

00:56:04.290 --> 00:56:06.240 align:middle line:90%
Animals have a sense of beauty.

00:56:06.240 --> 00:56:08.250 align:middle line:84%
I mean, think of
a peacock's tail,

00:56:08.250 --> 00:56:10.080 align:middle line:90%
think of a butterfly's wing.

00:56:10.080 --> 00:56:11.700 align:middle line:90%
Why are they so beautiful?

00:56:11.700 --> 00:56:13.440 align:middle line:84%
That's because
they are to attract

00:56:13.440 --> 00:56:15.350 align:middle line:90%
other members of the species.

00:56:15.350 --> 00:56:18.270 align:middle line:84%
They have a function, "the
beauty of sexual selection,"

00:56:18.270 --> 00:56:19.590 align:middle line:90%
as Darwin said.

00:56:19.590 --> 00:56:23.730 align:middle line:84%
But they wouldn't work unless
they had a sense of beauty.

00:56:23.730 --> 00:56:27.870 align:middle line:84%
And flowers are some of the
most beautiful things on Earth.

00:56:27.870 --> 00:56:30.270 align:middle line:84%
And again, as Darwin
said, "Before there

00:56:30.270 --> 00:56:32.970 align:middle line:84%
was an eye to see it there
could have been no flower."

00:56:32.970 --> 00:56:35.130 align:middle line:84%
There are interactions
between the plant

00:56:35.130 --> 00:56:36.960 align:middle line:90%
kingdom and the animal kingdom.

00:56:36.960 --> 00:56:39.820 align:middle line:84%
But they were there
70 million years ago,

00:56:39.820 --> 00:56:42.810 align:middle line:90%
long before any humans appeared.

00:56:42.810 --> 00:56:46.650 align:middle line:84%
And it was insect eyes that were
seeing the flowers, butterflies

00:56:46.650 --> 00:56:48.440 align:middle line:90%
and bees primarily.

00:56:48.440 --> 00:56:51.030 align:middle line:84%
They've evolved in
relation to insects.

00:56:51.030 --> 00:56:53.940 align:middle line:84%
And unless those insects
had a sense of beauty

00:56:53.940 --> 00:56:55.800 align:middle line:90%
with brains tiny--

00:56:55.800 --> 00:57:00.570 align:middle line:84%
really tiny brains, much,
much smaller than ours--

00:57:00.570 --> 00:57:03.330 align:middle line:84%
an exquisite sense
of beauty that

00:57:03.330 --> 00:57:06.980 align:middle line:84%
has driven the
evolution of flies,

00:57:06.980 --> 00:57:09.030 align:middle line:84%
then this shows that
a sense of beauty

00:57:09.030 --> 00:57:13.050 align:middle line:84%
is inherent in almost
anything, even in plants.

00:57:13.050 --> 00:57:16.050 align:middle line:84%
Fern leaves, for example, are
extraordinarily beautiful,

00:57:16.050 --> 00:57:18.450 align:middle line:84%
and that's nothing to do
with attracting insects.

00:57:18.450 --> 00:57:21.090 align:middle line:84%
It's just somehow
in nature itself.

00:57:21.090 --> 00:57:23.790 align:middle line:84%
There's hardly anything
ugly in nature itself.

00:57:23.790 --> 00:57:26.744 align:middle line:84%
Most ugly things we
see are man made.

00:57:26.744 --> 00:57:27.660 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Absolutely.

00:57:27.660 --> 00:57:30.630 align:middle line:84%
And yet we have cut
ourselves off from a lot

00:57:30.630 --> 00:57:32.380 align:middle line:84%
of the innate beauty
surrounding us.

00:57:32.380 --> 00:57:36.270 align:middle line:84%
We walk right by a beautiful
rose on the walkway,

00:57:36.270 --> 00:57:37.330 align:middle line:90%
for example.

00:57:37.330 --> 00:57:40.480 align:middle line:84%
This is something that
I have a hard time with,

00:57:40.480 --> 00:57:44.070 align:middle line:84%
is seeing the dismissal of
beauty on all its levels.

00:57:44.070 --> 00:57:46.980 align:middle line:84%
And so thank you for
sharing that perspective

00:57:46.980 --> 00:57:49.000 align:middle line:84%
from the animal
and insect kingdom.

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:53.790 align:middle line:84%
Let's go to the notion of
joining together as community.

00:57:53.790 --> 00:57:55.860 align:middle line:84%
And you do so in
your Anglican church.

00:57:55.860 --> 00:57:58.470 align:middle line:84%
And singing together and
what this does to the body,

00:57:58.470 --> 00:58:01.420 align:middle line:84%
because it actually
improves our immune systems.

00:58:01.420 --> 00:58:03.750 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about
chanting and singing.

00:58:03.750 --> 00:58:06.083 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, this is
something I've learned a lot

00:58:06.083 --> 00:58:09.540 align:middle line:84%
about my wife, Jill Purce, who
teaches chanting and singing.

00:58:09.540 --> 00:58:12.840 align:middle line:90%
Also, through singing myself.

00:58:12.840 --> 00:58:16.620 align:middle line:84%
When we chant or sing together,
we make notes together.

00:58:16.620 --> 00:58:18.870 align:middle line:84%
If we're chanting or
singing, we breathe together.

00:58:18.870 --> 00:58:22.530 align:middle line:84%
We literally come into
resonance with each other.

00:58:22.530 --> 00:58:26.760 align:middle line:84%
And if we're chanting or singing
mantras or standard prayers

00:58:26.760 --> 00:58:29.580 align:middle line:84%
or even regular
hymns, there's also

00:58:29.580 --> 00:58:32.310 align:middle line:84%
a resonance by what I call
morphic resonance with those

00:58:32.310 --> 00:58:33.760 align:middle line:90%
who've done it before.

00:58:33.760 --> 00:58:35.340 align:middle line:90%
So it's deeply connecting.

00:58:35.340 --> 00:58:37.230 align:middle line:84%
It connects us
with our own bodies

00:58:37.230 --> 00:58:40.770 align:middle line:84%
because the words make
our bodies vibrate.

00:58:40.770 --> 00:58:42.932 align:middle line:84%
It connects us
with other people,

00:58:42.932 --> 00:58:44.640 align:middle line:84%
and it connects us
with a whole tradition

00:58:44.640 --> 00:58:46.440 align:middle line:90%
of those who've done it before.

00:58:46.440 --> 00:58:49.630 align:middle line:84%
So it overcomes that
terrible isolation

00:58:49.630 --> 00:58:52.620 align:middle line:84%
that we fall into if
we cut ourselves off

00:58:52.620 --> 00:58:56.130 align:middle line:84%
from nature and from each
other and reconnects us.

00:58:56.130 --> 00:58:58.950 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And it's vibrating
inside our brains and inside

00:58:58.950 --> 00:59:02.260 align:middle line:84%
our bodies, healing us on a
very vibrational physical level.

00:59:02.260 --> 00:59:03.260 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Literally.

00:59:03.260 --> 00:59:05.292 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: How many of
us ever sing anymore?

00:59:05.292 --> 00:59:06.750 align:middle line:84%
Unless you happen
to hear something

00:59:06.750 --> 00:59:09.640 align:middle line:84%
in passing on the radio
that you know the lyrics to.

00:59:09.640 --> 00:59:10.440 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes.

00:59:10.440 --> 00:59:12.481 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And I mean, I
really feel this myself.

00:59:12.481 --> 00:59:14.970 align:middle line:84%
I stopped singing
for a long time other

00:59:14.970 --> 00:59:16.170 align:middle line:90%
than the occasional song.

00:59:16.170 --> 00:59:19.800 align:middle line:84%
And I've just been feeling
in the last year or two

00:59:19.800 --> 00:59:22.410 align:middle line:84%
that something is really
missing on a vibrational level.

00:59:22.410 --> 00:59:25.350 align:middle line:84%
So whether it's chanting,
whether it's spiritual,

00:59:25.350 --> 00:59:28.440 align:middle line:84%
whether it's for joy, we
just need to sing again.

00:59:28.440 --> 00:59:31.110 align:middle line:84%
And we can't go through
all of the points

00:59:31.110 --> 00:59:33.690 align:middle line:84%
because they're in your book
and very well delineated,

00:59:33.690 --> 00:59:36.990 align:middle line:84%
but I would like to go to
pilgrimage and the beauty

00:59:36.990 --> 00:59:41.520 align:middle line:84%
and value of pilgrimage and your
pilgrimages with your godson.

00:59:41.520 --> 00:59:44.430 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: Well, pilgrimage
is very ancient human thing.

00:59:44.430 --> 00:59:46.120 align:middle line:90%
All religions have it.

00:59:46.120 --> 00:59:49.330 align:middle line:84%
Our hunter gatherer ancestors
moved around the landscape.

00:59:49.330 --> 00:59:50.850 align:middle line:90%
They were nomadic.

00:59:50.850 --> 00:59:55.710 align:middle line:84%
And pilgrimage is like a residue
of our nomadic tradition.

00:59:55.710 --> 00:59:59.220 align:middle line:84%
I think it's deep and archetypal
to go to sacred places,

00:59:59.220 --> 01:00:02.460 align:middle line:84%
to reconnect with
those holy places.

01:00:02.460 --> 01:00:05.100 align:middle line:84%
The Protestant Reformation
abolished pilgrimage

01:00:05.100 --> 01:00:09.060 align:middle line:84%
in northern Europe, and the
settlers of North America

01:00:09.060 --> 01:00:12.750 align:middle line:84%
didn't have it because they were
Protestants for the most part.

01:00:12.750 --> 01:00:15.940 align:middle line:84%
The ones in South America,
the Catholics, included it.

01:00:15.940 --> 01:00:18.330 align:middle line:84%
They just took over the
ancient sacred places

01:00:18.330 --> 01:00:19.860 align:middle line:90%
and made them Christian.

01:00:19.860 --> 01:00:23.820 align:middle line:84%
So there are massive
pilgrimages in Catholic Central

01:00:23.820 --> 01:00:27.240 align:middle line:84%
and South America, for example,
to the shrine of Our Lady

01:00:27.240 --> 01:00:30.870 align:middle line:90%
of Guadalupe in Mexico.

01:00:30.870 --> 01:00:34.670 align:middle line:84%
So I've been doing this
every year with my godson.

01:00:34.670 --> 01:00:36.480 align:middle line:90%
We have a one day pilgrimage.

01:00:36.480 --> 01:00:40.080 align:middle line:84%
We walk the last eight
or nine miles towards one

01:00:40.080 --> 01:00:44.070 align:middle line:84%
of the great cathedrals of
England, Canterbury, Lincoln,

01:00:44.070 --> 01:00:48.600 align:middle line:84%
Wells, and what was
the other one we did?

01:00:48.600 --> 01:00:50.040 align:middle line:90%
Oh, Ely.

01:00:50.040 --> 01:00:54.190 align:middle line:84%
And this year, probably we're
going to go to Winchester.

01:00:54.190 --> 01:00:55.440 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Oh, it's beautiful.

01:00:55.440 --> 01:00:55.770 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

01:00:55.770 --> 01:00:57.330 align:middle line:84%
>> SHELDRAKE: So we walk
through the countryside,

01:00:57.330 --> 01:00:59.730 align:middle line:84%
connecting with the
countryside and each other,

01:00:59.730 --> 01:01:02.530 align:middle line:90%
relating to that holy place.

01:01:02.530 --> 01:01:04.410 align:middle line:84%
When we get there,
we go with intention.

01:01:04.410 --> 01:01:07.300 align:middle line:84%
We light a candle
and say a prayer.

01:01:07.300 --> 01:01:11.280 align:middle line:84%
Then we have a cream
tea, which refreshes us.

01:01:11.280 --> 01:01:13.650 align:middle line:84%
And then we go to
choral evensong

01:01:13.650 --> 01:01:17.670 align:middle line:84%
every day in all our cathedrals
on weekdays, not just Sundays.

01:01:17.670 --> 01:01:19.920 align:middle line:84%
There's this beautiful
evening service

01:01:19.920 --> 01:01:24.480 align:middle line:84%
in 16th century language sung
by wonderful choirs, called

01:01:24.480 --> 01:01:26.400 align:middle line:90%
choral evensong.

01:01:26.400 --> 01:01:28.080 align:middle line:84%
So we go to choral
evensong, which

01:01:28.080 --> 01:01:31.497 align:middle line:84%
is inspiring, uplifting,
incredibly beautiful.

01:01:31.497 --> 01:01:33.330 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Is that in
all Anglican churches?

01:01:33.330 --> 01:01:34.130 align:middle line:90%
>> SHELDRAKE: Yes.

